<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ensuring Economic Security Vital for FSB: Russian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko Monday said the Federal Security Service (FSB) faces the
serious task of ensuring economic security, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko made the remark as he introduced to the FSB collegium
its newly-appointed chief Vladimir Putin, who replaced Nikolai
Kovalyov last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It is particularly important for the service to ensure economic
security, and Putin's work in the presidential administration has
enabled him to gain knowledge and experience in combating economic
crimes, Kiriyenko said.
</P>
<P>
Putin, 46, a former employee with the USSR State Security
Committee (KGB), joined the presidential administration in 1996
and was appointed first deputy head in May 1997.
</P>
<P>
The premier said the replacement is not an indication of the
president's or the government's dissatisfaction with the work of
either Kovalyov or the service.
</P>
<P>
"Conditions are changing, people are changing," he said, and
Kovalyov's experience and capability "will continue to be used to
the Motherland's benefit."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the presentation ceremony, Kovalyov, the former FSB
chief, said the country's economic security, in particular
countering economic espionage and the illegal export of capital,
will be the most important job for the FSB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
