<HEADLINE> Boris Yeltsin Accused of Dissolving Soviet Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin was
accused on Monday by Russian lawmakers of causing the dissolution
of the Soviet Union in 1991 in order to seize and consolidate
power, the Itar-Tass news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a parliamentary commission on the impeachment of
President Yeltsin, lawmaker Viktor Ilyukhin said that Yeltsin
shared the blame with other republics' leaders who "did not have
the necessary status to sign those agreements and thus to
liquidate the USSR."
</P>
<P>
The Russian president's opponents insist that Yeltsin committed
high treason in signing the Belovezhye accords with other
republics that dissolved the USSR in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The accords can also be regarded as "illegal" because the 1922
Soviet Union founding treaty did not allow for its denunciation,
but only gave each republic the right to secede from the union,
Ilyukhin said.
</P>
<P>
"The Belovezhye agreements are an apparent violation of the
constitutional rights of all Russian citizens," Ilyukhin said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the consequences of these accords are so
grave that they should be the subject of a special meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Belovezhye accords were the first point on the five-point
indictment to be considered by the impeachment commission of the
State Duma, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian Constitution and the Duma's rules, the
commission can only recommend whether the president can face
criminal charges for what he has done.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary commission on impeaching Yeltsin will meet
again on august 17, Filimonov announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The action group has gathered 217 signatures under the
indictment, more than the required 150 signatures, commission
deputy head Yelena Mizulina said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
