<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing Home Sales Decline in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. resales of existing
single-family homes dropped 2.3 percent in June after posting a
record high in May, the National Association of Realtors reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decrease brought the seasonally adjusted sales rate to 4.72
million, down from 4.83 million, the highest since the association
began tracking sales in 1968.
</P>
<P>
Sales this year are being supported by unemployment near a
28-year low, healthy income growth, robust stock market gains and
low mortgage rates, which averaged 7 percent in June for 30-year
fixed-rate loans.
</P>
<P>
Fred Flick, the association's vice president for economic
research, predicted sales for all of 1998 would total around 4.54
million, 7.7 percent higher than 1997, when a record 4.21 million
homes were sold.
</P>
<P>
Regionally, the West recorded the largest drop in June, down
10.9 percent to an annual rate of 980,000 units. Sales also fell
in the Northeast, by 5.6 percent to a rate of 670,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Sales increased 1.7 percent to a rate of 1.2 million units in
the Midwest and 1.6 percent to a rate of 1.87 million units in the
South.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, the median sales price of an existing home was
134,600 U.S. dollars in June, up 5.8 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
