<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Fund Environment Projects in Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia-Herzegovina has become for
the first time a benefiting country of the European Commission's
environmental funding program, it was announced here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16 environment-related projects in Bosnia, Egypt,
Jordan, Cyprus and Lebanon as well as in the Baltic regions of
Kaliningrad and St. Petersburg will get 4.7 million ECU (5.1
million U.S. dollars) from the commission's finance instrument,
LIFE.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia will have EU funding for two projects.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission's funding will account for 78 percent
of the total cost of the 16 chosen projects aimed at assisting the
recipient countries to develop their environmental policies and
reinforce their national and local structures for the protection
of the environment.
</P>
<P>
Selected projects cover three areas of eligible actions:
technical assistance, nature protection and demonstration
activities, according commission officials.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, received for its environment funding 181 applications from
around the Mediterranean and the Baltic Sea, 50 percent more than
last year.
</P>
<P>
LIFE is the only EU financial instrument that provides aid for
the environment throughout the union and in the bordering regions
in the Mediterranean and the Baltic Sea.
</P>
<P>
The objective of LIFE is to contribute to the development and
implementation of EU environmental policy, by financing specific
environmental actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
