<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Ministry Employee Dismissed for Child Porn Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A Dutch Justice Ministry employee
was confirmed to have collected and stored child pornography
materials in the ministry's computer system, ministry sources said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The employee was already dismissed from his computer management
post in the general affairs administration department of the
Justice Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The case first came to light in April this year when another
employee of the department found child pornography materials on
computers and reported the finding to department management.
</P>
<P>
The employee who collected and stored the pornographic
materials was immediately suspended from his job and was dismissed
after police investigation was completed on July 17.
</P>
<P>
Ministry sources said that the employee in question was not a
senior ministry official as some Dutch press reports had
suggested.
</P>
<P>
The public prosecutor handling the case has possession of all
the documents and will now decide whether criminal prosecution
will follow.
</P>
<P>
Ministry sources also clarified that the case of the employee
was not linked to the current Zandvoort child pornography case
that was disclosed after a Dutch man was found killed in an
Italian town earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch authorities have expressed their determination to
clamp down on child pornography and Dutch police is conducting
investigation in close cooperation with its colleagues in
neighboring Belgium and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Battle Against Flooding Enters Crucial Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Anti-Flood efforts have entered a
crucial stage in central and eastern parts of China as several
provinces declared a state of emergency today and floodwaters
continued to rise on the country's largest river, Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
People are holding their breath as the third flood peak
passes. It is the second largest in the Yangtze Basin since 1954,
and the central government has called for a do or die effort in
protecting major cities and river and lake embankments and
ministries are being told to join the effort.
</P>
<P>
The State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters and
several ministries have sent teams to direct local flood-relief
work.
</P>
<P>
In Wuhan, capital of Hubei Province and the largest industrial
center in central China, and in Jiujiang, a tourist city in
Jiangxi Province, hundreds of thousands of people are watching the
river dikes and immediately repairing any minor defects that could
lead to breaches.
</P>
<P>
Citizens have been mobilized for the effort or asked to make
donations, says Jiujiang's Mayor Liu Shangyang. As of 1:00 pm
Monday, its citizens had collected over 60 million cubic meters of
stone, 20 million cubic meters of largerocks, 300,000 straw
sandbags and 200,000 chemical fiber sand bags.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 200,000 people have been evacuated to safe places in
southern Hunan Province, and local government offices have sent
food, clean water, medicines and tents to the flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 100,000 soldiers and armed police involved
in the struggle who the local press have lionized with the term
"suicide squads" because of the difficult and dangerous fight
against the rising waters. Military trucks, boats and aircraft
have been working day and night to deliver relief goods.
</P>
<P>
Medical workers have also joined the effort to prevent a
possible outbreak of epidemic disease. So far no cases have been
reported, even though the flooded areas have also been hit by a
heat wave.
</P>
<P>
People in other parts of the country have been offering help to
the affected areas. Shanghai, which is at the mouth of the Yangtze
River, have donated goods worth more than one million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
