<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Public Enterprises Minister Atef Ebeid said
Monday the government plans to sell 200 companies by the year 2000
either in full or in part to strategic investors or individuals
through public subscription.
</P>
<P>
He told the Middle East News Agency that 100 public sector
companies would be sold until 1999 and the rest by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Privatization is an essential part of Egypt's economic reform
program which started since Mubarak taking office in 1982. Egypt
is selling 10 companies every three months, and 105 out of 314
state-owned companies have been offered for sale under the
privatization program.
</P>
<P>
Egypt occupied the fourth place among 39 countries in terms of
efficiency of its privatization program according to an studay
issued by the International Monetary Fund in May.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian, Arab and other foreign investors have
obtained the approval of the Companies Administration in Egypt for
the establishment of a holding financial investment company, the
Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the company's authorized capital is 150 million
Egyptian pounds (44.7 million dollars), its issued capital 30
million pounds (8.77 million dollars), and its paid capital 20
million pounds (5.84 million dollars ).
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia is planning to construct 230,000 housing units
in the coming four years within the framework of the ninth
development plan which ends in 2001, the Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The volume of fund to be allocated for the housing sector under
the plan is estimated at 4.2 billion dinars (about 3.8 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian National Company for Maritime
Transport has turned from red into black by earning a net profit
of over 26 million rials (6.93 million dollars) in the first half
of this year, compared to the loss of 9 million rials (2.4 million
dollars) in the same period last year, the Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The company's General Manager Abdulla Al Sharim attributed the
positive results to the improvement of the performance and
productivity.
</P>
<P>
He said that the operational activities of the super oil
tankers had been improved, and an operational plan was introduced
to expand the company's market share. 
</P>
