<HEADLINE> China Grants Zambia $2.5 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China Monday granted Zambia 20
million RMB Yuan or 2.5 million U.S. Dollars for Zambia's
economic and technical activities.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here in Lusaka by Sun Guangxiang,
Chinese Vice-Minister for Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation,
who is heading a 19-member delegation, and Godfrey Simasiku,
Zambia's Deputy Minister of Finance and Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
China also agreed to assist Zambia in the feasibility study to
install FM radio broadcasting equipment as well as auxiliary
equipment for six provincial broadcasting stations in Zambia
through change of notes on the same occasion.
</P>
<P>
If the results of the feasibility study prove positive, the
two countries will sign another agreement for the implementation
of the project, according to Simasiku.
</P>
<P>
In a statement following the signing ceremony, Simasiku urged
the Chinese government and businessmen to invest in Zambia and
establish joint ventures with the Zambians in a bid to explore
the country's potentials in tourism, agriculture, mining,
manufacture, energy, communication and transport.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian deputy minister spoke highly of the existing
friendship between the two countries and expressed his "profound"
gratitude to China for granting the money.
</P>
<P>
In a brief speech, the Chinese vice-minister said China will
continue to assist Zambia and help it to establish medium and
small size productive projects which are lucrative.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese trade and economic delegation arrived in Zambia
Sunday following a three-day visit in Kenya. They will leave for
Zimbabwe Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
