<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hun Sen's Party Appears Set to Win Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Incumbent Co-Premier Hun Sen's
Cambodian People's Party (CPP) appeared set to win Sunday's
multi-party general elections, according to initial results
provided by the opposition Sam Rainsy Party Monday.
</P>
<P>
The CPP collected 50 seats in the 122-seat National Assembly,
to be followed by ousted First Prime Minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh's Funcinpec with 43 seats and former Finance Minister
Sam Rainsy's Sam Rainsy Party with 29 seats, the Sam Rainsy Party
said.
</P>
<P>
However, initial results have yet to be officially announced by
the National Election Committee (NEC), which postponed the
announcement, originally scheduled for Monday evening, until
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to initial results faxed to Xinhua by the Sam Rainsy
Party, the CPP collected a total of 451,567 votes, or 38.3
percent, while Funcinpec 442,019, or 37.5 percent, and the Sam
Rainsy Party 284,865, or 24.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under Cambodia's Constitution, a party needs a two-thirds
majority or 82 seats in the National Assembly to form a
government. Therefore, the CPP will have to form a coalition with
Funcinpec or the Sam Rainsy Party, or possibly even both, with the
CPP naming the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
But Ranariddh told Xinhua earlier in the day that he would not
work as deputy premier or whatsoever under Hun Sen, who deposed
him in July last year. The two men led a coalition government, a
product of the 1993 United Nations-organized election.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's election drew worldwide attention as it was highly
expected to give Cambodia a second chance for peace, stability and
a legitimate government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
