<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Open to Any Peace Initiative: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides said Monday his government welcomes any peace initiative
on solving the Cyprus issue, either from the U.N. Security Council
or the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Clerides made the remark in a statement issued in response to
criticism from the left-wing opposition Working People's
Progressive Party (AKEL) on the government's handling of the
peace talks and its plan to deploy Russian missiles.
</P>
<P>
"We accepted and will accept any initiative from the Security
Council or any EU member state, and always weigh up their
interests in relation to Turkey on one hand, and on the other,
their aim for a lasting and steady solution to the Cyprus
problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
AKEL's General Secretary Demetris Christofias has strongly
criticized the government for failing to break the impasse in the
Cyprus peace talks, charging it for "putting all its eggs in one
basket" by relying on only the United States.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that he would accept a U.S. initiative on Cyprus,
but would not accept anything that would endanger the Cypriot
people's future or would not bring about a fair, just and viable
solution.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the S-300 surface-to-air missiles Cyprus ordered
from Russia in January 1997, Clerides said they would increase
the country's air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his government would not bow to threats over
the missile issue although it was well aware of the the
international reaction. "The government handles this reaction
responsibly, without giving in to threats," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and EU have criticized Cyprus' plan to deploy the
Russian missiles, while Turkey has threatened to launch preemptive
strikes against the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to settle the Cyprus problem reached a stalemate in
last August when Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out
of a U.N.-sponsored direct peace talks between the two Cypriot
communities following a EU decision to start accession talks
with the Clerides-led Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has announced he would not return to the peace talks
unless his breakaway regime in northern Cyprus is recognized and
Cyprus halts its accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
