<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission Investigates Killings in Northeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- United Nations mission in Angola
will continue to investigate in the killings last week in
northeast Angola's Lunda-Norte Province.
</P>
<P>
The investigation team, which went to the scene of violence
last Saturday to seek information from local leaders, will once
again set for Bula Town in the province for further probe,
according to David Wimhurst, spokesman for the U.N. mission after
the joint committee meeting of Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
Reports said militiamen of the opposition National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) launched attack last
Friday in Bula Town, Lunda-Norte Province, killing over 150
unarmed civilians and wounding dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
However, Horacio Junjuvile, deputy chief of the UNITA
delegation to the joint committee, denied UNITA's involvement in
the killing and demanded that the U.N. mission further
investigate in the event so as to determine the true killer.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman revealed that representatives of the United
States, Russia and Portugal as well as the U.N mission held talks
with the signatories of the Lusaka peace accord Monday to discuss
issues regarding returning national authority to UNITA controlled
areass of Bailundo, Andulo, Mungo and Nharea and complete
demilitarization of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
However, Wimhurst said, the two sides still disagreed over the
issues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, media reports said UNITA forces continued to launch
military operations around the country. On Sunday, UNITA
militiamen took over Coxe Town in Bengo Province, 60 km from the
capital Luanda.
</P>
<P>
Local officials disclosed that during the UNITA operations,
36,000 people have become new refugees in Bengo Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
