<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Government to Sell 5% Gazprom Stake in Full </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Under a Russian president's decree
the Russian government will sell five percent of its stake in the
gas giant Gazprom in full, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin last Saturday signed a decree
to sell five percent of the natural gas monopoly Gazprom, while 35
percent of the Gazprom stock would remain state property, in order
to boost state coffers while keeping the company under state
control.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said in Kaliningrad
that "five percent is just the right figure that will enable us to
do that without harming the country or the company."
</P>
<P>
Vice-president of the Gazprom Pyotr Rodionov told a press
conference on Monday that the Gazprom management knew about the
preparation of corresponding presidential instructions and
recommended the sale of the five percent stake in full.
</P>
<P>
In Rodionov's view Gazprom may reduce, within three years, the
production and supply of gas for domestic consumption from over
300 billion cubic meters to 80 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
CEO of Gazprom Rem Vyakhirev said that tentative talks must be
held with Gazproms's strategic partners, Royal Dytch Shell and
ENI, on the sale of the five percent Gazprom stock held by the
state.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to obtain the largest possible amount of money for
the federal budget and to keep the company's shares from sliding
on the stock market, Vyakhirev's press secretary Gennady Yezhov
said.
</P>
<P>
The state currently holds 40.9 percent of Gazprom, which
produces 94 percent of Russia's gas and accounts for a quarter of
all the gas produced throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom, according to Russian officials, owes the government
about 12 billion rubles (2 billion U.S. dollars) in back taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Knesset Rejects No-Confidence Motions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Two days before its summer
recess, Israeli Knesset (Parliament) Monday rejected three
no-confidence motions against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Despite the voting result of 42-20, the motions, tabled by the
opposition Labor, Meretz and Hadash parties, still failed to pass
due to the lack of the 61 votes needed in such vote.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli law, the government has to step down if a
no-confidence motion is passed by a majority of 61 votes in the
120-seat Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-led coalition is having a slim 61 majority in the
Knesset.
</P>
<P>
In the no-confidence motions, the opposition parties blamed the
government for the prolonged deadlock of the peace talks with the
Palestinians that began since early last year.
</P>
<P>
They also accused Netanyahu of leading the country to a
disaster through his hard-line policies in the negotiations with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been stalled since March last year when
Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement in the
traditionally Arab East Jerusalem. The talks are currently stuck
over Israel's delay in carrying out the second further withdrawal
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Monday's vote was regarded by Labor and Meretz as a prelude to
two bills they will present for the preliminary reading Wednesday
calling for the dissolution of the Knesset and holding early
elections.
</P>
<P>
Only a simple majority is needed in the preliminary reading
on the two bills, but their passage through the three readings in
the next Knesset session still requires the absolute majority of
61 votes.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset will reconvene on October 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
