<HEADLINE> Italian PM Urges Turkey, Greece to Better Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi Monday called on Turkey and Greece to make efforts to
improve their bitter relations, according to the Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Prodi made the call at a joint press conference with his
Turkish counterpart Mesut Yilmaz in Turkey's largest city of
Istanbul, where he was on a one-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that concrete steps must be taken to decrease the
current tension in Cyprus, and urged Yilmaz and Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis to make a difference in that respect.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is damaging the economies of both Greece and
Turkey and increasing the military spending of the two
countries," said the Italian prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), have long been at odds over a number of
disputes such as the Cyprus issue, air space limit and right of
sea-bed mineral resources in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Early last week, Yilmaz visited northern Cyprus, where Turkish
Cypriots had declared a breakaway state, to attend a ceremony
marking the 24th anniversary of the Turkish military intervention
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The visit again prompted strong protests from Greece and
Cyprus, with which the European Union (EU) has begun negotiations
in order to bring it into fold.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Turkey's tension with the EU, Prodi said that
his country supports Turkey's bid to become a full EU member.
"Turkey and the EU are obliged to go together in the long run. The
destiny is for cooperation and mutual understanding," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkey-EU relations worsened after Turkey cut off political
dialogue with the EU to protest that it was excluded from EU's
first enlargement plan.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Yilmaz said Turkey welcomes Italian businessmen's
participation in its energy and defense projects as well as its
huge privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also discussed the deteriorating Kosovo
crisis, and called on the international community to prevent a
new war in the Balkan region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
