<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Images Confirm Sign of  Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Satellite images from the
world's coldest continent Antarctica have confirmed the rapid
melting of a key Antarctic glacier, a 20-mile-wide river of ice
whose retreat could eventually lead to the collapse of major ice
sheets and a resulting rise in global sea levels.
</P>
<P>
After studying satellite data collected from 1992 to 1996, Eric
Rignot, a radar scientist at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
California, have come to the above conclusion, The Washington Post
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Pine Island Glacier is often described as the "soft
underbelly" of the Western Antarctic Ice Sheet because it is
exposed to relatively warm South Pacific waters and is thought to
be especially vulnerable to rising temperatures.
</P>
<P>
Their new research shows the glacier is indeed shrinking at
remarkably fast clip, retreating inland at the rate of about a
half-mile a year.
</P>
<P>
They said still unclear is whether the melting is due to
human-induced global warming or other factors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
