<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colonial Powers Blamed for Burundi Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A Burundian rebel leader
said Monday in Arusha, north Tanzania, that colonial powers
perpetuated ethnic division in the central African nation and
significantly contributed to the current civil strife there.
</P>
<P>
Presenting FROLINA (the Front for National Liberation)'s views
on the genesis of the Burundi conflict, the Hutu rebel group's
leader, Joseph Karumba, said German and Belgian rulers in history
perpetuated the domination of Tutsi and discriminated both the
majority Hutus, accounting for 85 percent of the country's
population, and Twa which represents one percent.
</P>
<P>
Burundi was ruled by Germany between 1886 and 1914 and later
by Belgium during 1914 and 1962.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Karumba said the
colonialists deliberately favored Tutsis, whereas the Hutus and
Twa, were mistreated and disregarded.
</P>
<P>
"The Belgians enforced the discriminatory system by
maintaining the Tutsis in a privileged status," he alleged,
adding that education was only offered exclusively to Tutsi
children and Tutsis were favored with social, economic and
political advantages.
</P>
<P>
The Belgians ruled with a similar system, he said at the
plenary session of Burundian peace talks chaired by international
peace facilitator, Julius Nyerere, former president of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsis, he added, were described by colonial rulers as
wise, intelligent, lovely and good-looking people, while Hutus
were relegated as unwise, ignorant, unkind and unfaithful
peasants.
</P>
<P>
Karumba also said that during different historical periods from
King Mwami to the current leadership of military strongman Pierre
Buyoya, Hutus have been systematically excluded or killed to make
Tutsis dominate the political, economic and social scene of
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Burundians have to change their ideas in order to remove the
Hutu-Tutsi barrier, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to remove our ethnic differences which were long
associated with conflicts, and which too often led to dangerous
political arguments for the priority of one group and negligence
or even suppression of the others," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader suggested 14 points to end ethnic violence in
Burundi, including recognizing the dignity and rights of all
Burundians, encouraging Burundians to reaffirm their commitment
to fundamental human rights.
</P>
<P>
He also said Burundi should recognize international legal
organizations so as to implement human rights, and abolish
negative laws and practices.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, People's Reconciliation Party (PRP), one of the
parties at the talks, said that absence of a king in Burundi had
led to such brutal ethnic violence. Sylvestre Ntibantunganya,
former president of Burundi, claimed that previous insincerity of
governments had plunged the land-locked Burundi into
unprecedented crisis between Hutus and Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
Twelve parties, rebel groups and two former presidents of
Burundi have made their statements on the nature of the conflict
in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere's spokesman, Brigadier General Hashim Mbita, said five
more parties will give speeches on Tuesday morning to wind up the
agenda of debate on the Burundi conflict.
</P>
<P>
He also said the other item on the agenda adopted last week,
the issue of rules for the negotiation procedure, may be ready by
Tuesday for discussion by all warring parties.
</P>
<P>
"The talks have made substantial progress and we hope to wind
up the Burundi conflict debate tomorrow," Mbita told reporters at
the end of the sixth day of peace talks at the Arusha International
Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
The talks bring the government of Pierre Buyoya, who took
power in a July 1996 coup, face to face with Hutu rebels who are
fighting the country's Tutsi-dominated army.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Strengthens Control Through Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister Tony Blair
made the first reshuffle of his cabinet on Monday since Labor
swept to power 15 months ago by sacking four ministers.
</P>
<P>
Social Security Secretary Harriet Harman, one of the most
high-profile women in the cabinet and role model for middle-class
New Labour feminists, were out of the cabinet office.
</P>
<P>
Also dismissed were the government's leader in the House of
Lords Ivor Richard, public services minister David Clark and
transport minister Gavin Strang.
</P>
<P>
The major ministers in the cabinet all kept their jobs --
Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, Home Secretary (interior
minister) Jack Straw, Foreign Secretary Robin Cook and Education
Secretary David Blunkett.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair's key aide and minister without portfolio,
Peter Mandelson, takes over the Department of Trade and Industry,
according to Blair's official spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson, a pro-European rightwinger with close links to
business, replaces Margaret Beckett, who will stay in the cabinet
as leader of the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary Jack Cunningham, a veteran Labor
politician, was given a new job co-ordinating the work of the
cabinet and resolving disputes between ministries. His job will be
replaced by Nick Brown, who has up to now been government chief
whip, responsible for discipline in Labour's House of Commons
ranks.
</P>
<P>
Baroness Margaret Jay, daughter of 1970s Labor prime minister
Lord Callaghan, enters the cabinet as government leader in the
House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
Alistair Darling, chief secretary to the Treasury, is promoted
to be new Social Security Secretary.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Byers, currently Schools Standards minister, will join
the cabinet as Chief Secretary to the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
John Reid moves to be transport minister from defense ministry,
where he was armed forces minister.
</P>
<P>
The government spokesman said Blair's aim was to strengthen the
center of his government.
</P>
<P>
Under party rules, Blair had been obliged to choose his first
government from the "shadow cabinet" elected by Labor members of
parliament while they were in opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
