<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Rebel Leader Calls for Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's rebel leader Foday
Sankoh, sent back home for trial from more than one year's
detention in Nigeria, has called on his supporters to cease fire
and make peaceful dialog with the government.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, who appeared on the state television in handcuffs at
the weekend, condemned atrocities against civilians blamed on his
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels and remnants of the
military junta forces, according to a report reaching here Monday
from Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal to RUF rebels and junta to cease fire immediately
and let us talk peace," Sankoh said.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the civil defense force known as Kamajors, loyal
to President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, to do the same.
</P>
<P>
"You see the RUF and the Kamajors must stop the fighting
against the people. And I think we can solve our problem in
peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh appeared on television with Information Minister Julius
Spencer after Nigeria flew him back to Sierra Leone earlier in
the day, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The RUF leader was arrested and put into house arrest in March
1996 when he arrived in Nigeria ostensibly on a peace mission.
</P>
<P>
Following his arrest, a division arose within the RUF ranks on
whether to continue or abandon the rebellion the armed group
launched since 1991 against successive governments.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Sankoh, some 40 soldiers of the former Sierra
Leonean armed forces are already on trial for treason in
connection with their role in the May 25, 1997 coup which ousted
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
The junta, which named Sankoh the number two person of the
country, was toppled in mid-February this year.
</P>
<P>
The trial will resume Tuesday. It was unclear when Sankoh,
whose trial had been predicted by officials before his
extradition, would appear in court.
</P>
<P>
The remnants of the junta and allied RUF rebels are still
holding parts of mineral rich areas in the east and north of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led west African peacekeeping force, which
restored Kabbah's government in March this year, is stepping up
its mopping up exercise for an early wipe out of the forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
