<HEADLINE> Turkey Blasts Switzerland for Kurdish Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Monday condemned
Switzerland for permitting the convening of an anti-Turkish
meeting in the Swiss city of Lausanne by Kurdish rebel groups,
the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a written statement that the
Swiss decision displayed its "unfriendly attitude" toward Turkey and
would undermine the Turkish-Swiss relations.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn the Swiss federal government for the insensitive
stance it has adopted on anti-Turkish activities in its country,
despite repeated warnings from Turkey," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Several Kurdish groups organized an anti-Turkish rally Friday
in Lausanne where the historical Lausanne Treaty was signed in
1923 marking the founding of modern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Lausanne Treaty replaced the 1920 Sevres Treaty which
envisaged the establishment of an autonomous Kurdish region in
southeastern Turkey and a final independent Kurdish state.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Lausanne municipal authorities
rejected a request from the Turkish Embassy to hold a celebration
ceremony marking the 75th anniversary of the signing of the
Lausanne Treaty in a palace where the document was inked.
</P>
<P>
Swiss officials said that such an official ceremony might
provoke protests from the Kurds and Armenians living in the
neutral European state.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry described the Swiss government's
refusal to allow the celebration on the 75th anniversary of the
Lausanne Treaty as "incomprehensible and unacceptable." 
</P>
