<HEADLINE> AL Chief to Visit Libya on Lockerbie Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Ahmed
Esmat Abdel-Meguid will visit Libya next week for talks on the
latest developments of the Lockerbie issue, the Egyptian Middle
East News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid told reporters that he will discuss with the
Libyan side "all aspects of the Libya-West crisis" and a plan of
Arab action aimed at settling the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
Two Libyans have been suspected of bombing a Pan Am jetliner
over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, killing 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have demanded that the two
suspects be tried in either of the two countries. Fearing that its
citizens would not receive a fair trial, Libya insists that they
be tried in a neutral place.
</P>
<P>
In an about-face gesture, the U.S. and Britain agreed last week
to have the two Libyans tried in the Hague, the Netherlands. The
development has been hailed by the Arab League as a "diplomatic
and political victory for the Arab world."
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said "the talks in Tripoli will take up ways of
lifting the international sanctions imposed against Libya,
particularly after the U.S. and Britain accepted an Arab proposal
to have the two Libyan suspects tried in a Dutch court according
to the Scottish law."
</P>
<P>
He sent a message on Monday to the United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan, expressing the league's readiness to cooperate
with the world organization in dealing with the Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to fully cooperate with the United Nations in
facilitating the mission of all parties concerned to reach a
peaceful settlement to the issue, guaranteeing the rights of all
parties and leading to lifting the sanctions off Tripoli," he said
in the message.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed air and arms embargo against
Libya in 1992 after Tripoli refused to hand over the two suspects
for trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
