<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Urged to End Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- President Hassan Gouled Aptidon
of Djibouti and President Daniel arap Moi of Kenya Monday urged
Ethiopia and Eritrea to cease hostilities and honor the decision
by the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
"As neighbors of Ethiopia and Eritrea, Kenya and Djibouti are
gravely concerned with the conflict which is a threat to peace in
the region," the two presidents said in a joint communique issued
following their talks here.
</P>
<P>
All the four countries are members of the Inter-Governmental
Authority on Development (IGAD) which also groups Uganda, Somalia
and Sudan. Aptidon, who paid one-day visit to Kenya, has
replaced Moi as the rotating IGAD chairman.
</P>
<P>
"An IGAD heads of state and government summit would be
convened after submission of the OAU report in order to determine
further direction on the conflict," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, OAU said Monday it would
present its report this week on a fact-finding mission into a
border dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The report is expected to comment on where the borders lay and
who administered the territory before the dispute began.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Moi held talks here respectively with
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and his Eritrean
counterpart Isaias Afwerki. However, no breakthrough was made.
</P>
<P>
Moi's move was seen as the latest of a series of international
mediation efforts since border clashes erupted between the two
Horn of Africa countries on May 6.
</P>
<P>
Tensions escalated in early June when the two sides bombed
each other and battles raged for a brief period on three fronts.
Hundreds were killed before fighting gave way to a stalemate on
the border where thousands of troops are massed on each side.
</P>
<P>
In June, Eritrea rejected a proposal by the U.S. and Rwanda to
end the fighting. Further attempts by African heads of state
from Burkina Faso, Zimbabwe and Djibouti also made little
headway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
