<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Asylum Seekers May Be Allowed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Up to 30,000 asylum seekers may be
allowed to stay in Britain, Home Secretary Jack Straw announced on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
As part of this process, most of the 10,000 people who have
been waiting for five years for an initial ruling would be allowed
to stay in Britain indefinitely, Straw's office said.
</P>
<P>
"The delay in reaching a decision would normally be considered
to be such a significant factor that indefinite leave to remain
would normally be appropriate," it said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the cases of 20,000 people who arrived between
July 1993 and the end of 1995 would be reviewed under a
"streamlined" system.
</P>
<P>
But Straw said in the parliament that he planned tougher
treatment for new arrivals in the future, including assigning them
accommodation while their cases were assessed.
</P>
<P>
About 75,000 people are waiting for a decision on applications
to British immigration officers for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
A large proportion of them have been in Britain for years,
either waiting for hard-pressed immigration officers to process
their claims, or going through a complex appeals system.
</P>
<P>
Straw said he was stepping up government funds devoted to
processing claims with the aim of ending the backlog by April,
2001.
</P>
<P>
Successive governments have been battling to cope with
increasing numbers of asylum applications from people arriving and
claiming to be at risk if they return home.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
