<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-27 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Announces Tariff Cuts for WTO Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to win entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO), Sudan has decided to cut
taxes and custom duties, Sudanese Finance Minister Abdel-Wahab
Osman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a press conference, Osman said the decision would
take effect in six months when Sudan adopts a law on taxes, which
outlines the details of the tax reform.
</P>
<P>
He said the average custom duties would be first lowered to 80
percent and finally be replaced by consumption taxes to protect
domestic products.
</P>
<P>
Sudan would continue the process of lifting all the customs in a
bid to meet WTO's demands, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his country would cancel the 19 percent
tariff on imported goods and a number of domestic products. The
tariff includes the 4 percent protection tax, 5 percent service
tax and 10 percent consumption tax.
</P>
<P>
Sudan would exempt some products and services from import and
export tariffs, including wheat, pesticide, medicine, milk,
insurance, education and medical services, Osman said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the new tax policy was aimed at protecting the
domestic industry, ensuring national revenues and offsetting the
negative effects on the Sudanese people caused by the country's
entry to WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
