<HEADLINE> WFP Calls for Funding for Emergency Food Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program Monday issued an urgent appeal to increase its funding so
as to expand emergency food aid to war and drought-torn southern
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"We will need a great deal of help from the donor community if
we are to prevent an all-out famine in Sudan," said WFP Executive
Director Catherine Bertini in a news release reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came at a time when the food crisis in Sudan
continues to worsen, especially in the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based U.N. food aid agency said recent mass movements
of people in search of food and safety in southern Sudan have
increased the demand for food.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial reports indicate that up to 80 people are dying of
malnutrition each day in Wau, the capital of the Bahr el Ghazal
region, said WFP.
</P>
<P>
WFP now estimates that its emergency food requirement amounts
to 129,000 tons against the original estimate in April of about
82,500 tons. WFP is targeting 2.6 million people throughout
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
WFP is appealing to donors to provide food worth 154.5 million
U.S. Dollars for its operations until April 1999. So far, donors
have pledged over 40 percent of that, leaving a shortfall of
57,651 tons valued at 92 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of July, WFP has delivered more than 7,800
tons of food by air and road convoy to needy Sudanese and plans
to deliver another 3,000 tons by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The food relief agency expects to deliver up to 15,000 tons of
food each month from August and has increased its fleet of cargo
aircraft from eight to 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
