<HEADLINE> China's City to Get Award for Habitat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Once a poor fishing village,
Zhuhai, in southern China, has become a model city in the world for
comprehensive environmental management amid rapid urban growth,
the U.N. Center for Human Settlements (Habitat) announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zhuhai, together with other nine cities, has been selected by
an independent international jury to receive the prestigious
Dubai International Award for best practices in improving the
living environment, said the Nairobi-based Habitat.
</P>
<P>
Other nine cities are Medellin of Columbia, Cairo of Egypt,
Surat of India, Arabuko-Sokoke of Kenya, Xalapa of Mexico, Naga
City of the Philippines, Malaga of Spain, Dar-es-Salaam of
Tanzania and Kennesaw in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Best practices and the experience they embody provide a
strong building block for new policies, strategies, and even
paradigms for the effective governance and efficient management
of human settlements in the 21st century," said Jury Chairperson
Arcot Ramachandran.
</P>
<P>
According to a Habitat press release, best practices are
the initiatives undertaken by governments, local authorities and
civil society, that have made outstanding contributions to
improving the quality of life in urban and rural communities.
</P>
<P>
Most of the best practices reviewed by the jury are
contributing directly to poverty eradication, gender equity and
equality and social inclusion.
</P>
<P>
Each award winner will receive a 30,000-U.S.-Dollar prize, a
trophy and a commemorative certificate. An award-giving ceremony
will be held in Dubai to coincide with the global celebrations of
World Habitat Day on October 5.  
</P>
</TEXT>
