<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Tele-Conference On Closing Down Army's Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A Standing Committee member of the
Communist Party of China Central Committee's Political Bureau and
the Central Committee Secretariat, Hu Jintao, has said that
China's armed forces, the armed police and judicial organs need to
understand the importance of the recent decision to stop all the
businesses they run.
</P>
<P>
Hu told a tele-conference of the CPC Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection and the CPC Central Committee Political
Science and Law Committee here today that the central authorities'
decision was a major step in building the Party and the army in
the new conditions and in continuing the anti-corruption
campaign. It is also important for safeguarding the socialist
market order and the country's stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
If they engage in business, he said, the powerful army, the
armed police and law-enforcement departments could become a hotbed
of corruption. Some of their units have been involved in illegal
activities like smuggling and the sale of smuggled goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
This would certainly harm the image of the army, armed police
and law-enforcement departments, Hu said, and asked them to put
the nation's and the people's interests above anything else.
</P>
<P>
The central government says that the army, the armed police and
law-enforcement departments need to clear up their business
connections as soon as possible, and in future, should not be
involved in any commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the anti-corruption work in the army, the
armed police and law-enforcement departments to protect their very
nature, Hu explained.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, also a member of the Standing Committee of the
CPC Central Committee Political Bureau and Secretary of the
Central Discipline Inspection Commission, talked about discipline
and rules for the anti-corruption efforts.
</P>
<P>
The army, armed police and law-enforcement departments are
prohibited from hiding, relocating, transferring or selling
properties belonging to enterprises they run, or from distributing
funds and property belonging to firms held privately under any
name, and from making false financial reports, or rewriting,
hiding or destroying financial documents belonging to the firms,
Wei said.
</P>
<P>
He said that no employee of these companies should be
transferred to other units or promoted to higher posts and that
anyone suspected of being involved in criminal cases will be
stopped from going abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding In Central China: Past and Present </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- At eight o'clock this morning, the
waters of the Yangtze River near the city of Wuhan rose to a
dangerous 28.8-meter high, but the 286-kilometer embankment remained
intact and the city breathed a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
On the very same day in 1931, the water rose to 28.3 meters,
breaching the embankment, and covering three districts of Wuhan
for more than 100 days. The disaster took the lives of 3,619
people and left 630,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains of the past several months have turned the
area into one of the country's worst flooded spots. On July 25,
water levels in the large industrial center climbed to 28.3
meters, surpassing the 1931 record. On the third day, it rose
another 0.5 meter.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze, whose embankments put it above the surrounding
area, was as much as 6 meters above the downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
Surprisingly however, while the waves battered the embankments,
the city went about business as usual, and there was no price
gouging, because supplies held.
</P>
<P>
Xu Shaohua, a 58-year-old shop owner, was still at his shop near
the Wuhan Dock, with the water only 50 meters away. "I'm sure the
embankment will hold and my business has not been affected at
all," he said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants and entertainment centers along the river remained
open and lovers strolled beneath the neon lamps as usual.
</P>
<P>
But, 67 years ago, the place where Mr. Xu's stall stands, was
in the middle of the Yangtze and the Dock's clock tower was an
island.
</P>
<P>
As the city became inundated, survivors were looking for
shelter on a few dry high spots, only to face the prospect of
wide-spread famine and disease.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers at the time wrote: "The more than 23,000 hungry
people are so miserable that people don't even dare look at them."
</P>
<P>
Huang Lizhen, who turns 84 this year, tells of a narrow escape
thanks to a boat and has a vivid memory of the past. He lives 100
meters from the embankment and believes that history will not
repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
His trust may be justified. It was only 100 kilometers long 67
year ago, but today stretches 286 kilometers, and as the water
rises, it also goes up, thanks to flood-control efforts.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have spent 560 million yuan (67 million
U.S. dollars) on the levee, increasing it from 108 kilometers in
1949 to 286 kilometers, and a 157-kilometer section is 2 meters
higher than the highest water level of 1954.
</P>
<P>
And, a reinforced concrete water-proof wall has been built in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Wang Weichun, the author of "A History of the Embankment of
Wuhan", calls the 1931 catastrophe both a natural and a man-made
calamity.
</P>
<P>
According to historical reports, when people reported to He
Chengjun, the governor of Hubei Province, that the embankment had
burst, he said, "It doesn't matter much. Just do what you see
fit," and then went back to playing mahjong.
</P>
<P>
Today, the flooding is a major concern of the central
government. President Jiang Zemin gave directions over the phone
when Wuhan was flooded on July 21, calling for an all-out efforts.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji has toured several flooded provinces and
cities and Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao came to Wuhan today when the
third flood crest passed the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs More Biologists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- China needs to educate more
biologists for the next century, some scientists and educators say.
</P>
<P>
The 21st century is regarded as the life science century, and
today's middle school students will face the task of developing
China's biological technology, says Wu Guangyao, professor of
Beijing University's Institute of Life Science, who just returned
from Germany with four Chinese middle school students who won
three gold and one silver medal in the International Olympiad of
Biology in Germany.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for Chinese students to win since China
began to participate in the contest in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The four prize winners have been recruited by Beijing
University and Qinghua University without being required to take
the entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jing, one of the champion, says that she is mostly
interested in genetics and wants to study it at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
However, scientists and educators say the contest results don't
represent the whole situation in China.
</P>
<P>
Biology is not included in the college entrance examination at
present, and Song Daxiang, president of the China Zoological
Society, says that Chinese education departments need to pay more
attention to biology.
</P>
<P>
Song says that biology textbooks in China's schools lag far
behind biological developments in the world and that middle
schools give students theory and play down experiments.
</P>
<P>
He says this is mainly because of the government's lack of
spending and the lack of good laboratories.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Zengyi, a basic education official with the Ministry of
Education, says that the ministry will increase spending on
biology teaching and build more modern labs in middle schools.
</P>
<P>
In some pilot cities like Shanghai and Guangzhou, biology will
be included in the college entrance exams again.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that some farsighted enterprises have begun
training biologists. Denmark's Novo Nordisk, which produces
insulin and industrial enzymes, has set up scholarships at Beijing
University, Qinghua University and Nankai University to help the
better students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
