<HEADLINE> Chinese Young Ambassadors Work For Sino-U.S. Relations (1) by Liu Yunfei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese middle school
students left here today for the United States to make new friends
to build Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
This follows the agreement reached by President Jiang Zemin
and President Clinton on promoting people-to-people exchanges
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang said during his U.S. visit last fall that the
most important thing in bilateral relations is to enhance mutual
understanding between people.
</P>
<P>
At Beijing University earlier this month, President Clinton
told students that the younger generations of both countries not
only have the responsibility of shaping their respective futures,
but also need to contribute to the growth of the bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 Chinese youngsters, mostly coming from Beijing,
Shanghai and Hainan, will travel to Hawaii, New York, Washington
D.C., and Los Angeles to take part in two speech contests entitled
"China and the U.S. in My Eyes".
</P>
<P>
"The growth of Sino-U.S. relations in the future depends on the
youth of the two countries," says Yu Shilian, who is head of the
Chinese student delegation and serves as deputy director-general
of the Department of American and Oceanian Affairs of the Chinese
People's Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries, an
organization for people-to-people exchanges in China.
</P>
<P>
She says that more communication between youngsters in the two
countries will undoubtedly help bilateral relations geared to the
21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
