<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Urged to Help Lift Sanctions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf Tuesday reiterated the call for a unified
Arab stance on the lifting of U.N. economic sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq always calls for a stronger Arab stance to help lift this
ban, especially after Iraq (has) honored its commitments towards
the U.N. Security Council resolutions," al-Sahhaf told reporters
after meeting with Arab League chief Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister arrived here on Monday en route to Rabat,
Morocco, to attend a ministerial meeting of the Jerusalem
Committee of the Conference of the Islamic Organization on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf said that he exchanged views with Abdel-Meguid on
means of activating a common Arab action in seeking to lift the
"unjust" U.N. embargo.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has imposed crippling economic
sanctions on Iraq since 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait, banning
the export of oil, Iraq's main income earner,
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, al-Sahhaf briefed Abdel-Meguid on the
relations between Baghdad and the U.N. special commission for
disarmament in Iraq, or the UNSCOM, which is in charge of
overseeing the elimination of Iraqi weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
He accused the UNSCOM of creating pretexts aimed at prolonging
the crippling embargo against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler last week blamed Iraq for
blocking arms inspectors' verification of its report on the
chemical and biological weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions can only be lifted after the UNSCOM
certifies that Iraq has destroyed all its nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons and long-range missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
