<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Gains 3.8 Pct Economic Growth in 1st Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE July 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong said Tuesday evening that his country managed a
modest 3.8 percent of economic growth in the first half of this
year but the economy is continuing to decelerate.
</P>
<P>
All sectors except construction have been affected by the
regional economic crisis that continues to worsen, he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a presentation ceremony of the
International Trade Awards conferred to companies that showed
healthy performances in their businesses.
</P>
<P>
Referring trade as a sensitive indicator of the regional
problems on Singapore, the deputy prime minister said his
country's overall export in the first half of the year saw little
expansion as exports to regional economies, namely Japan, South
Korea, Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia and Hong Kong, have fallen
sharply. These six economies traditionally bought almost half of
Singapore's exports.
</P>
<P>
He noted Singapore's exports to the other half of its global
market, particularly in the U.S. and EU, grew by 17 percent in the
first half compared to the first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hsien Loong said: " our highly and globalized economy makes
us specially vulnerable to the vagaries of the external
environment."
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing more retrenchments and business reorganization
taking place this year than usual," he said.
</P>
<P>
On restructuring the service sector deemed to be affected more
severely than the manufacturing by the regional crisis, the deputy
prime minister said there is some urgency in promoting and
developing the service sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that Singapore still lags behind other hub in
significant areas despite being headquarters to over 120 trading
companies. "We are unlikely to overtake London, New York or
Frankfurt. But we should firmly position ourselves as a premier
services hub in Asia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
