<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Food Tender Notice Angers Somalis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) published a tender notice Tuesday, angering a lot
of Somalis including the local health authorities, magistrates as
well as politicians in the capital here.
</P>
<P>
WFP has published a tender notice on all newspapers here for
the sale of 152 tons of dry pea beans unfit for the human
consumption stored in both sides of the capital and in the port
town of Merca, 100 kilometers south of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The tender notice clearly states that the buyer of the pea
beans is expected to sign a letter of indemnity absolving WFP of
any responsibility after the commodity which has an odor and was
declared unfit for human consumption is collected from the WFP
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
WFP said that the buyer must use his or her own bags for the
beans instead of using the WFP marked bags.
</P>
<P>
North Mogadishu faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed has strongly
condemned WFP for its sale of the expired pea beans to the
Somalis.
</P>
<P>
"It's a total degradation to the Somalis," said Mahdi who was
briefing the reporters in Mogadishu Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said it's unfortunate that many Somalis had recently died
of hunger following the floods and droughts that hit southern
Somalia while WFP was keeping its pea beans in the warehouses
until it became unfit to be consumed.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi blamed the aid agencies, such as WFP, on sending
poisoned relief food to the Somalis.
</P>
<P>
"WFP is even trying to avoid the responsibility by announcing
that the WFP marked bags will not be used by the buyers of the
commodity as if this responsibility will go beyond their feet,"
said Mahdi.
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu's Joint Health Authority (JHA) has strongly reacted
and condemned WFP for ignoring the health of the already
malnourished Somalis.
</P>
<P>
Osman Mohamud Dufle, the JHA coordinator, told the reporters
here Tuesday that the pea beans of WFP are neither fit for the
human being nor for the livestock as well.
</P>
<P>
The commodity is already having different fungi which endanger
the liver of the people and sometimes bring about liver cancer as
well, Dufle said.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator has called on WFP not to sell this commodity
to the Somalis who will immediately take the pea beans to the
markets for people's consumption.
</P>
<P>
"There's a total anarchy in the country," Dufle said, adding
that "if the aid agencies cannot help the Somalis, let them not
hurt us at least."
</P>
<P>
Mogadishu's health authority has also called upon WFP to
withdraw its tender notice and either to bury the pea beans or
set fire to them or else get them out of the country so as to
avoid any danger which can be traced back to the prestigious
agency, WFP which has helped thousands of Somalis.
</P>
<P>
JHA has urged the Somali businessmen not to buy the pea beans
which WFP itself had declared unfit for the human consumption.
</P>
<P>
A group of Somali magistrates led by Abdulkadir Sheikh Ma'ow
have similarly condemned WFP for its sale of the expired
commodity.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ma'ow said that WFP will still be liable despite its
meager attempts to remove all of its traces from pea beans.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ow said that it's up to WFP to find a more suitable way of
getting rid of the pea beans.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he said, WFP won't escape the legal consequences of
any health hazards created by its tender.
</P>
<P>
The magistrates have called on WFP to cancel its tender so as
to defend the prestige it has attained during the past seven
years of civil strife among the Somalia's warring parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Telecom Says AT&AMP;T-BT Deal Challenges China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The recent deal between AT&AMP;T and
BT, two of the world's leading telecommunications companies, will
further intensify competition on the international market, a China
Telecom official said today, and that China is watching
developments closely.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T and BT announced on Sunday that they will form a
10-billion-U.S.-dollar global venture that combines the
international operations and networks of the two companies.
</P>
<P>
The China Telecom official, who spoke anonymously, said that
the move marks a new trend in the competitive telecommunications
service market.
</P>
<P>
With combined international networks, the two companies can
extend services to 237 countries and link 100 cities with a
network that transmits voice and data at a rate of 200 gigabites
per second.
</P>
<P>
Both companies are major partners of China Telecom. AT&AMP;T
handles more than 50 percent of the United States' telephone
traffic with China, while BT handles over 60 percent of that
between Britain and China.
</P>
<P>
China signs a separate agreement with every foreign company
that uses the country's telecommunications network for telephone
services and fees are charged according to each agreement. China
also has its own charges on international telephone calls made
from China.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T has three offices with 62 employees in China. It
cooperates with China Telecom in telephone services to and from
the U.S., and provides telephone card, tele-conference, and frame
relay services.
</P>
<P>
A China Telecom official says that although China has begun to
break up its telecommunications monopoly by setting up a second
national telecommunications company, Unicom, the country's
telecommunications service still cannot match foreign companies in
terms of quality, scale, efficiency, and cost.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
