<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Prime Minister to Reshuffle Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister Radu
Vasile is expected to reshuffle his cabinet, merge ministries and
is also planning to make cuts, the National Monitor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle is expected to take place after August 15 and no
later than September 1 when the parliamentary session begins,
governmental sources were quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a program including urgent economic
measures will be completed By August 15 and will serve as the
ruling program for the reshuffled government.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, ministers and secretaries of state, or vice
ministers, will be scaled down in number while some ministries are
expected to merge, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Among the possible mergers are the Industry Ministry with the
Tourism Ministry, the Agriculture Ministry with the Environment
Ministry and the Transportation Ministry with Public Works and
Territorial Planning Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the council for reform will be annulled, leaving
only one ministry in charge of privatization and reform.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also plans to assign a secretary of state to
co-ordinate the privatization and reform under his direct
supervision.
</P>
<P>
Some ministers are expected to lose their portfolios in the
reshuffle, while others will be assigned as secretaries of state.
</P>
<P>
Officially, neither the government nor the coalition parties
are speaking about governmental changes, but coalition sources
said Prime Minister Radu Vasile has already contacted some
coalition parties to checkout the reaction to his plans.
</P>
<P>
The Radu Vasile cabinet came into being in April in the wake of
a three-month political crisis in Romania that culminated with the
resignation of Victor Ciorbea, Vasile's predecessor.
</P>
<P>
The government has been pressed with unpopular austerity
policies aimed at overhauling the troubled economy, which
witnessed a surge in inflation from 57 percent in 1996 to over 100
percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
