<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Bank of Israel has announced that it will cut
the interest rates by 0.3 percentage points in August to 11
percent, Israel's Haaretz daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This will be the seventh consecutive monthly cut this year,
with the interest rates having been cut by 2.4 percentage points,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that it has decided to cut the interest
rates again because the inflation rate is remaining low.
</P>
<P>
Since the current government came to power in 1996, the
central bank has reduced the interest rates by 6 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The World Bank has estimated that Syria has to
spend more than 35 billion Syria liras (700 million U.S. dollars),
or 4.5 percent of the gross national product, to improve its
environment, the Arab-language daily Al Hayat reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank has said the shortage of potable water, lack of public
health services and pollution has led to a loss of 12 billion
liras (240 million dollars) in Syria.
</P>
<P>
It said the Syrian economy may provide more than 24 billion
Syrian liras (480 million dollars) to mobilize the necessary
financial resources for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has disclosed that Syria's approval of an
enviromental plan of action will help it get international
financial aid.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Authority for Investment and Free Zones
Monday announced the establishment of the Egyptian Company for
Petroleum Industrialization, Egypt's Alam Al Yom reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first company set up in Egypt for petroleum
production and refining.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank of Egypt, Misr Bank, Alexandria Bank, Cairo
Bank, and other banks and companies have a share in the company's
capital of 1.02 billion Egypt pounds (300 million dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
