<HEADLINE> Thai Businessman Unhappy About U.S. Judgment on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 28 (Xinhua) -- One of Thailand's leading
businessmen Tuesday called "funny" the U.S. ban on imports of Thai
shrimps in the name of the latter's inappropriate protection of
sea turtles, saying judgment must be done fairly.
</P>
<P>
"Every human being has the responsibility to protect our earth,
but no one can judge others by their own limited knowledge,"
Khemmadhat Sukondhasingha, Secretary General of the Federation of
Thai Industries, told Xinhua after the inauguration of the
Greening of Industry Network (GIN) - Asia here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said most of Thailand's exported shrimps are grown in shrimp
farms instead of fishing from the sea.
</P>
<P>
So it was "funny" that the United States launched a ban on Thai
shrimps and quoted Thailand's fishing of shrimps harming the lives
of sea turtles as the reason, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Judgment (on the environmental issues) must be done fairly,"
Khemmadhat said.
</P>
<P>
As for environmental issues in Thailand, Khemmadhat said the
country's industries, especially those heavily polluting ones,
like chemical industry, have been making efforts to address the
environment problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has made policies, encouraging the
industries to protect the environment. For example, the government
allows tax exemption for enterprises which import machines that
would reduce pollution, he said.
</P>
<P>
Khemmadhat joined some 250 participants from governments,
universities and non-governmental organizations (NG0s) to
celebrate the establishment of the Asian node of the GIN in
Thailand's oldest and most famous university, Chulalongkorn
University, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1991, GIN has grown to nearly 1,500 individuals
who represent government ministries, research institutions,
corporations and NGOs from 50 countries. It is a research and
policy network that focuses on issues of industry, environment and
society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
