<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Russia Launch Environmental Monitoring Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Russia, Britain, France and
Germany launched a global environmental monitoring program Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first tangible step of the European Union-Russia
space venture since they agreed to cooperate in July last year.
</P>
<P>
The four countries, represented by the Khrunichev State
Research and Production Space Center, Matra Marconi Space and
Daimler-Benz Aerospace, signed a protocol on forming a consortium
to provide monitoring service within four or five years.
</P>
<P>
The consortium, named Global Environmental Service (GES), is
expected to provide continuous global information on environment
for governments, regional and local public decision makers, as
well as the private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Edith Cresson, European science commissioner, said the EU is
concerned about damage done by industries to the fauna and flora
as well as to public health, and would like to have as many means
as possible for observation.
</P>
<P>
She said that other European space industries can also join in
the open cooperation program.
</P>
<P>
Yuri Koptev, director-general of the Russian Space Agency,
promised that the space cooperation would get comprehensive state
assistance from the Russian side and that effective cooperation
would spill over to other industries like navigation and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Matra Marconi representative Jean-Luc Lagardere said the space
cooperation would serve as a bridge between Russia and the EU as
far as space technology expertise is concerned.
</P>
<P>
The GES, though still in the feasibility study phase, is
expected to build and launch its own satellite system, as well as
benefit from existing satellites, be it weather forecast
satellites or military ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
