<HEADLINE> Australian Flood Relief For China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government will
provide over 150,000 Australian dollars in emergency assistance
for flood victims in central and southern China, the Australian
Embassy in China announced today.
</P>
<P>
Since early June, many parts of China, especially a dozen
provinces and regions south of the Yangtze River, have been hit by
heavy rains, leading to serious flooding and causing enormous
losses of life and property.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze is now approaching its seasonal peak and the
provinces of Hubei, Jiangxi and Jiangsu are facing renewed threats
of flooding.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Embassy said that Alexander Downer, Australia's
Foreign Affairs Minister, extended his sympathy for the flood
victims on behalf of the Australian government to his Chinese
counterpart Tang Jiaxuan on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The assistance is mainly intended to help those who are in
urgent need of food and medical supplies and will be provided
through the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.
</P>
