<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Canadians Experience High Cancer Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Eastern Canadians are more likely
to develop cancer and die from it than residents of the three
westernmost provinces, a new study from Statistics Canada claims.
</P>
<P>
Cancer and mortality rates vary widely across Canada, but the
number of cancer victims is significantly lower in Canada's three
westernmost provinces -- Saskatchewan, Alberta and British
Columbia, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
There is less variation in the rate of incidence and mortality,
which is about 10 percent below the national average in
Saskatchewan and below 5 percent in British Columbia and
Alberta. Cancer among women is highest in Nova Scotia, about 7
percent above the national average.
</P>
<P>
Mortality rates from cancer are about 10 percent below the
national average for men in the three westernmost provinces. In
Nova Scotia, the rate for men is 13 to 16 percent higher than the
national average. In other eastern provinces, it is about 5
percent higher.
</P>
<P>
More men suffer from cancer nationally than women. In the study
period from 1991 to 1993, 476 new cases were diagnosed per 100,000
men, compared with 337 per 100,000 women, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The figure translates to about a 40 percent greater incidence
of cancer and a 60 percent higher mortality rate for men than
women, largely because of the difference in the rate of lung
cancer -- 89.4 cases per 100,000 men, compared with 43.2 cases per
100,000 women.
</P>
<P>
Smoking is believed to be responsible for 85 percent of all
lung cancer and perhaps 30 percent of other cancers.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 35 percent of all cancer is linked to dietary
factors, the report notes. 
</P>
