<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Manufacturing Output Declines in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing output
 declined by 0.9 percent in June from the same month last year as
higher output in the chemicals cluster was offset by declines in
the electronic and engineering clusters, the Economic Development
Board (EDB) said in a press release Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the June drop, cumulative output for the first half of
this year was 2.2 percent higher than the same period in 1997, EDB
said.
</P>
<P>
The country's manufacturing output has shrank for the second
consecutive month after May saw a 4.5 percent fall over the month
last year.
</P>
<P>
According to EDB's press release, the chemical cluster
(including petroleum, petrochemicals, pharmaceuticals and
specialty chemicals) grew by 23 percent compared to June 1997 and
the growth was contributed solely by the pharmaceuticals segment
that shot up by 108 percent with a rise in newer pharmaceutical
products.
</P>
<P>
The press release said that the output from the electronics
cluster sank by 7.1 percent as a result of lower output of
computers, disk drives, consumer electronics and telecommunication
equipment.
</P>
<P>
EDB said a combination of factors -- excess supply, declining
prices, dwindling demand, and relocation of production --
adversely affected the production of the electronics cluster.
</P>
<P>
Compared with June 1997, output of petroleum products in June
1998 declined by 2 percent and the petrochemicals industry
contracted by 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Output from the engineering cluster contracted by 5.2 percent
as the precision engineering segment shrank by 15.7 percent
despite a 18.6 percent rise and a 4.9 percent growth in process
engineering and transport segments respectively.
</P>
<P>
EDB attributed the contraction in the engineering cluster to
the declines in the electronics cluster that continued to depress
the output of metal and plastic precision components, tools and
dies and connectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM: Indian Nuke Tests Run Counter to Trend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan denounced Indian nuclear tests in May as "running counter
to the trend of the world" when he met with Deputy Chairman
Jaswant Singh of the Indian Planning Commission at the latter's
request here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In what a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman described as
"frank discussions" on the Indian nuclear explosions and
Sino-Indian ties between the two sides Monday evening, Tang said,
"India, flagrantly running counter to the world trend, conducted
the nuclear tests, thus undermining peace and stability in South
Asia and the international safeguards against nuclear
proliferation."
</P>
<P>
"It is only natural that the international community has
strongly denounced such an act," Tang was quoted by the
spokeswoman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both Foreign Minister Tang and Deputy Chairman Singh are here
attending meetings of the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) and
Post-Ministerial Conference (PMC) between July 27 and 29. Their
countries are ASEAN's dialogue partners at the ARF and PMC.
</P>
<P>
"More infuriating is the fact that India, in its effort to find
an excuse for the tests, groundlessly alleged that China poses a
threat to India," the Chinese foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"These are sheer fabrications which have poisoned the
atmosphere surrounding the Sino-Indian relations and seriously
harmed Sino-Indian ties," Tang said. "This is something that China
does not wish to see," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that the Chinese government has always followed a
foreign policy of good-neighborliness, under which it is ready to
establish and develop friendship and cooperation with all its
neighbors including India.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that in recent years, the Chinese side has
made tremendous efforts to improve and promote relationship with
India, he said.
</P>
<P>
He held the Indian side responsible for the problems which have
cropped up in the relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"In China, we have the saying, 'A knot can be untied only by
the person who tied it'," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the Indian side respects the common aspirations of the
international community, accept and carry out the benchmarks set
forth in U.N. Security Council Resolution 1172, abandon its
nuclear weapons development plan, sign the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty, join the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of
Nuclear Weapons and take concrete actions to improve Sino-Indian
relations."
</P>
<P>
Singh at the meeting explained India's views and stressed that
his country's nuclear tests were not directed at any country,
according to the Chinese spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the Indian government's hope for better relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tang also met separately with Brunei Foreign
Minister Prince Mohamed Boldiah, Lao Foreign Minister Somsavat
Lengsavad and Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer Monday,
the spokeswoman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
