<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Asks to abolish Illegal Levies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
Tuesday asked the Office of the State Minister for Investment to
abolish all kinds of illegal levies that could discourage
investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We should create a conducive climate for national economic
development," Habibie told a meeting between the Investment
Coordinating Board and its provincial branches at the State Palace
here.
</P>
<P>
The president asked the Office of the State Minister for
Investment to provide fresh information on business opportunities
open in the country's provinces so that they could be offered to
domestic and foreign entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Habibie also asked the office to initiate special measures that
would bring back capital that had been taken out of the country
following unrests and prevent more capital flight.
</P>
<P>
"Capital flight indicates that our business sector has yet to
recover," he said.
</P>
<P>
On efforts to encourage businessmen to reinvest their capital,
Habibie emphasized the need to reassess the country's investment
system and introduce incentive and disincentive policies for
investments.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the biggest challenge faced by the people
and the government is how to make the wheel of economy start
turning again.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has rich natural and human resources, Habibie said,
adding that bringing in investment would restart business, secure
the supply of basic commodities, open jobs and resume national
development.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Investment and Chairman of the Investment
Coordinating Board Hamzah Haz said investments have been low in
recent years, mainly due to the openness of the global economy as
well as the social and political unrest in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and foreign investments from April 1994 to June 1998
reached only 126.24 trillion rupiah (12.6 billion U.S. dollars),
or 56 percent of the 6th Five-Year Development Plan's (from 1994
to 1999) target of 224.70 trillion rupiah (22.4 billion dollars),
he said. 
</P>
