<HEADLINE> Volkswagen to Pass On Name Rights of Rolls-Royce From 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Europe's largest automaker Volkswagen
AG (VW) announced Tuesday in Wolfsburg that its German rival BMW
AG would acquire the rights to the name `Rolls-Royce' beginning in
2003.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding between the two
German companies, VW will retain the name until the end of 2002
and then concentrate exclusively on the development, production
and distribution of Rolls-Royce's sister brand Bentley.
</P>
<P>
VW will also rename the Rolls-Royce Motor Cars Ltd in Crewe,
northwest England, as Bentley Motor Cars Ltd after 2002.
</P>
<P>
BMW will deliver engines and components to VW's Rolls-Royce
Motor Cars subsidiary until December 2002, the documents said.
</P>
<P>
VW acquired Rolls-Royce Motor Cars Ltd with 1.44 billion marks
(about 770 million U.S. dollars) last month, but the rights to the
name remained in the hands of Rolls Royce Plc, which had an engine
deal with BMW.
</P>
<P>
BMW will acquire the rights to the Rolls-Royce brand name from
Rolls Royce Plc and pass it on to VW for exclusive use until the
end of December 2002.
</P>
<P>
The Rolls-Royce "Silver Seraph" will continue to be produced in
Rolls-Royce's Crewe plant with BMW engine supplies. From 2003, BMW
will produce Rolls-Royce cars at a new plant.
</P>
<P>
Chiefs of the two companies and Rolls-Royce Plc will provide
more details in London on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
