<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Chinese Provinces Report HIV/AIDS Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The figure of reported HIV/AIDS
cases in China has surpassed 10,000 and all 31 Chinese provinces,
autonomous regions and municipalities have been plagued, according
to the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Total cases of HIV - human immunodeficiency virus which causes
acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS) - reached 10,676 by the
end of June, including 301 fully-developed AIDS patients, the
ministry's Department of Disease Control said today.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Qinghai Province has no longer been "the
nation's last AIDS-free province" since some cases were found late
last month, said Xiao Yan, an official with the department.
</P>
<P>
AIDS experts fear that most of HIV/AIDS cases have not been
reported due to limited surveillance scale. "The true number may
have reached some 300,000," Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
The experts blame the rapid epidemic of the disease on rampant
drug abusing with contaminated syringes and prostitution. They
have warned that the HIV figure would rise to one million at the
beginning of the next century without immediate and effective
preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
Drug users accounted for two thirds of the infected, and
sufferers of sexually transmitted diseases and illegal blood
sellers run the increasing risk of infection, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
