<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia: Less Expatriates Allowed in Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Saudi cabinet has approved
regulations to reduce the number of expatriates working in
government institutions so as to give native Saudis a better
chance to get employed, Kuwait News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, approved on Monday night, came in line with a
Saudi strategy drafted on the basis of reducing the number of
non-Saudis to make room for the indigenous work force in the
government sector.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations stipulated that concluding or renewing any
contract with a non-Saudi government staff should be handled by
the highest authorities.
</P>
<P>
The new policy said an expatriate's contract with the
government should not exceed 10 years. But in case of dire need
for services of certain skilled expatriates on duty like health
sector and university staff members, an exception to this
stipulation can be made.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulations, to renew an expatriate's
contract, the government authority should advertize for the
vacancy in local media three months prior to the required date to
ensure that no qualified local citizen wants the job.
</P>
<P>
In order to limit expatriates in the public sector, the Saudi
government adopted a five-year plan in 1995 which called for
employing 660,000 Saudis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aragones Quits as Real Betis Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MADRID, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Luis Aragones has quit as coach of
Spanish first division club Real Betis on Tuesday in Seville,
Spain.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released before his 60th birthday, Aragones
said: "On Saturday I handed my resignation to the president for
personal reasons."
</P>
<P>
Aragones didn't elaborate his surprise decision, only saying
that he will retire from soccer.
</P>
<P>
Betis' president Manuel Ruiz de Lopera confirmed that
Aragones' decision was purely personal.
</P>
<P>
Aragones, who has coached over 600 League games, was
previously forced to quit in Betis for health reasons in the
1981-82 season.
</P>
<P>
Aragones is the second coach resigning from a Spanish first
division side in the summer. On July 9 Jose Antonio Camacho quit
Real Madrid though he won the European Cup title for the club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
