<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Iraq Exchange Remains of Dead Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Iraq on Tuesday swapped
remains of 100 Iranian and 83 Iraqi soldiers killed during the
1980-88 Iran-Iraq war, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The exchange took place at the border point of Shalamcheh,
Iran's southwestern province of Khuzestan, the report said,
adding that the remains of Iranian soldiers were found inside
Iraq following joint search operations of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In May, the two former enemies started their joint search for
remains of dead soldiers close to their common borders. In June,
the two sides exchanged remains of 53 Iranians and 134 Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed on Monday to continue their joint
search operations for those missing in actions (MIA) during the
1980-88 war.
</P>
<P>
Tehran and Baghdad have agreed to speed up their efforts to
solve the issues of MIAs and prisoners of war (POW) as they are
still the main hurdles for the two countries to normalize their
relations.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officials recently announced that Iran and Iraq could
close the files of POWs within six months as the two sides showed
their sincerity in solving their issues.
</P>
<P>
But it is believed that the issue of MIAs would need more
time since the joint search operations advance slowly due to the
mines and other explosives in former battle fields in the border
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
