<HEADLINE> Donation Received for Flood Hit Area in Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Salvation Army Hong Kong
Command Headquarters Tuesday received the first batch of goods
donated by Hong Kong companies for people in flood stricken areas
in China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Envoy Simon Wong of the Hong Kong Salvation Army told reporters
Tuesday afternoon that 54 boxes of biscuits, 300 boxes of instant
noodles and some other food and medicine were received on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the donation began on Sunday and a total of
300,000 HK dollars (38,462 U.S. dollars) of fund has been received
so far.
</P>
<P>
Wong said that many residents and companies have called them in
the past few days to ask how to donate for the people in the flood
hit areas.
</P>
<P>
The goods will be sent to Hunan province next week and the
donation will continue, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Hong Kong Salvation Army has applied for 4.8
million HK dollars (615,300 U.S. dollars) in relief fund from the
government and it will collect millions of HK dollars of donation.
The donation will be used to buy food, medicine and tents for the
people in the flood stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The Salvation Army is an international religious and charitable
movement with a distinctive military style in its structure and
operation. It is an integral part of the protestant Christian
Church. 
</P>
</TEXT>
