<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Election Draws Different Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 28 (Xinhua) -- As international observers gave
a nod to Sunday's polling in Cambodia, four parties on Tuesday
refused to accept the vote result because of what they called
"irregularities."
</P>
<P>
"We have observed many irregularities in the polling, counting,
and reporting of election results," said a joint statement issued
by Prince Norodom Ranariddh's Funcinpec Party, the opposition Sam
Rainsy Party (SRP), the Cambodian Neutral Party and Son Sann Party.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot accept the result of these elections until these
irregularities have been seriously investigated and proven by
national and international observers to be nothing more than minor
technical errors," the statement said, putting into question the
election's legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP) led by incumbent
Co-Premier Hun Sen was leading in votes, followed by Funcinpec and
the SRP, according to partial results announced by the Cambodian
National Election Committee (NEC).
</P>
<P>
Complete initial results would not be available until August 1,
the NEC said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, international observers monitoring Sunday's polling
and on-going vote counting said the election was "free and fair,"
fueling hopes that the election could be a success.
</P>
<P>
The Joint International Observer Group (JIOG) said in a
statement that its impression on the polling day and the counting
day was "a process which was free and fair to an extent that
enables it to reflect, in a credible way, the will of the
Cambodian people."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the assessment was based on the reports
received from the JIOG's almost 500 international observers in the
field.
</P>
<P>
"A consolidated statement will be made at a later stage, when
these observers have been debriefed after their return to Phnom
Penh and their full reports have been thoroughly analyzed," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the reports received by the JIOG thus far "have been in
the main encouraging" and the climate on the polling day and
counting day "was peaceful and calm."
</P>
<P>
"In general, the polling achieved democratic standards and on
the day it appears that people felt able to vote without fear of
reprisal," it added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the International Observer Team led by former U.S.
Congressman Stephen Solarz and former U.S. ambassador James Lilley
also acknowledged the same impression.
</P>
<P>
They said in a statement that the voting and counting processes
"were generally well administered, and the atmosphere on the
balloting and counting days was largely peaceful and upbeat."
</P>
<P>
But the opposition SRP said in a separate statement that "it
would be terribly irresponsible for any organization to draw
conclusions on the validity of this election before a full
evaluation is completed and made public."
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh reportedly complained about fraud in voting
and counting, demanding polling again in some areas, or he would
not accept the result.
</P>
<P>
The historic election, which was expected to give the nation a
chance for peace, stability and a legitimate government, saw a
voter turnout of more than 90 percent, a much higher figure than
expected.
</P>
<P>
The CPP, Funcinpec and the SRP are expected to dominate the new
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Since not a single party will be able to win a required
two-thirds majority, or 82 seats, to form a government, a
coalition will be formed with the largest party, most likely the
CPP, naming the prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Flood-Fighting on Yangtze Dikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of local people in
Honghu City, which sits on the northern bank of Yangtze River,
worked around the clock to reinforce river dikes as the third
flood crest passed through the city on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reports of Luoshan Hydrologic Station show that the water
level there has surpassed the record level by 0.27 m. to climb to
34.44 m. yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shunde, a 56-year-old man in Luoshan Township, said on his
way back home after a night-long hardwork at the embankment, "How
could I sleep at home when flood comes to my doorsteps."
</P>
<P>
He reviewed that the river section at Zhoujiazui faced the
danger of breach as water level rose rapidly early this
morning. Some 600 officers and soldiers of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army joined 1,500 local people and rushed to repair the
dangerous sections and brought the peril under control.
</P>
<P>
A villager is now seen positioned every 10 meter on the main
embankment of Yangtze River to keep a close watch over flood
development.
</P>
<P>
An inspection team headed by officials at various levels
conducted blanket patrol three times a day on the 135-km-long
embankment in the city, said Zhang Xinshe, a local government
official.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 residents in Baota Village have been evacuated to
safer places before the village was swallowed by the first flood
crest on July 3. They are living in 200 simply-built huts.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5,000 people were blocked by floods. Some live at
primary schools and others at government buildings.
</P>
<P>
A villager named Tian Shoucheng said, "We lack no confidence
though we temporarily lost our home."
</P>
<P>
Water conservancy experts say the fight against flood has
entered the crucial stage because water level at many tributaries
of the Yangtze has surpassed the record height. Moreover, there
might be more rainfalls in the region over the next few
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
