<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Kills Israeli Allied Militiaman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Israeli allied
South Lebanon Army (SLA) was killed Tuesday morning by a roadside
bomb in south Lebanon, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was planted and detonated by guerrillas of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, in the Beit Yahun
village in the western sector of the Israeli occupied south
Lebanon, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
In response, Israeli artillery troops and its proxy SLA
pounded the surrounding villages, leading to the slight injury of
a 70-year-old Lebanese civilian in the Ber Ashit village.
</P>
<P>
Some civilians' houses and cars were also damaged during the
attack, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the 2,000-strong Israeli troops and the SLA have
come under attack by Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
In addition, heavy losses the Israeli forces suffered during
the past decade have increasingly raised question in Israel about
the wisdom of maintaining troops in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In April, Israel has offered to withdraw from the region on
condition of Beirut's security guarantees for its northern borders.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria have rejected the offer and demanded
the Jewish state leave Lebanon without any preconditions as
stipulated in the 20-year-old U.N. Resolution 425. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
