<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level on Poyang Lake Stops Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The water level on Poyang Lake in
east China's Jiangxi Province remained stable at 22.36 meters from
8 am to 2 pm today due to less rainfall in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the flow rate of incoming water into the
lake dropped from 23,000 cu.m/second on Sunday to 16,500
cu.m/second currently. Meanwhile, the flow rate of outgoing water
from the lake fell from 8,400 cu.m/second to 2,000 cu.m/second,
according to the Flood Control Headquarters of Jiujiang city.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there would be no substantial rainfall in
the area in the coming two days, which will have less effect on
the water level of the Yangtze River's main streams.
</P>
<P>
However, the lake's water level is still high, with water
levels registered at four local hydrological stations rising more
than three meters above danger levels. And nearby four counties
have been partially flooded.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River's third flood crest is expected to pass the
Jiujiang River on Wednesday, where local hydrological station
recorded a water level of 22.85 meters at 2 pm, 0.06 meters higher
than six hours before. But the growth rate was dramatically lower
than on Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
