<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Beefs up Flood-Control Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The flood-control headquarters of
Shanghai municipality has issued an urgent call to beef up the
effort to counter floods and typhoon.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Shanghai has been sweltering hot and sunny in recent
days and there has been little precipitation. However, since the
end of the what is called the plum rain season on the traditional
Chinese lunar year calendar and particularly following July 23 and
24, there have been torrential rains and downpours, resulting in
the submerging of streets. Water has entered the homes of 2,600
families.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, the water level in Shanghai has been rising
rapidly, with the tidal levels at the upper reaches of the
Huangpu River and the lower reaches of Suzhou River exceeding
the official safety lines.
</P>
<P>
A leading official of the municipal flood-control headquarters
said that Shanghai has entered a period of frequent torrential
rains, typhoons, cyclones and hailstone.
</P>
<P>
A second round of tropical tempests or typhoon may affect
Shanghai in August or September, the official said.
</P>
<P>
These factors, when joined by floods running down to the lower
reaches of the Yangtze River, could possibly result in big
flooding in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Keen attention should be paid to weather changes and the
central control system for water drainage have to be improved, the
flood-control headquarters said.
</P>
<P>
"We should neither slack our vigilance nor be off alert for the
sake of ensuring the safety of local residents and Shanghai
economy," according to the urgent call.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
