<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Urged to Rebel Against Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Africans should rebel
against political instability, coups and anything that placed the
continent in a bad light, South African Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki said in Swakopmund, Namibia Monday night.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at a dinner for delegates to the second
Southern African International Dialogue forum in the Namibian
coastal town, South African Press Association reported Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
"We must rebel against this because if something goes wrong in
Somalia, the residents Mississippi, in the United State of
America do not say something has gone wrong in Somalia... They
say something has gone wrong in Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Africans were mutually dependent on each other. The smart
partnership would therefore be for Africans to get together and
say it was incorrect for anybody in the continent to steal a
presidency.
</P>
<P>
"And therefore as governments, to say what is it that we can
do to ensure that that doesn't happen."
</P>
<P>
Political parties, religious leaders, trade unions and all other
sectors of society should be committed to this objective.
</P>
<P>
Because of the interdependence between African countries, it
was important that they discussed and understood the challenges
of the modern economy so that they were able to take their place
in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki called for African countries to devise ways of dealing
with the so-called YK2 problem or millennium bug, the disruption
of computer systems as their internal clock reset.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of South African Telecommunications Minister Jay
Naidoo, Mbeki announced that an Southern African Development
Community forum would be held on August 18 or 19 to discuss and
coordinate ways of addressing YK2 problems.
</P>
<P>
The venue for the forum was not announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
