<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrean President Wraps Up Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean President Issayas Aferwerki
left here Tuesday morning for home following a two-day visit to
Egypt during which he discussed with the Egyptian leadership a
worsening border dispute in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Aferwerki arrived Monday in the Egyptian northern resort of
Alexandria for talks with President Hosni Mubarak on the ongoing
efforts to restore peace to the Eritrean-Ethiopian border where
clashes erupted in May.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif told reporters
Monday that the two leaders have thoroughly thrashed out the
different aspects of the dispute and the proposed solutions to
bring it to a halt and encourage peaceful coexistence between the
two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean president, who had sent two messages to Mubarak in
June, has been seeking an active role from the Egyptian leader in
halting the developing Ethiopian-Eritrean border conflict.
</P>
<P>
But recent remarks by Egyptian officials suggested that Cairo
is not going to spearhead the mediation effort despite repeated
appeals from both sides.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the last leg of his current African tour which also
took him on Sunday to Tripoli, where he met with Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi on the latter's proposal for setting up a buffer
zone on the Eritrean-Ethiopian border.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Eritrean Minister of External Affairs
Haile Woldensae said in Pretoria, South Africa, on Monday that
Asmara is willing to accept unconditional ceasefire as a prelude
for initiating direct dialog with Ethiopia on their border
strife.
</P>
<P>
In a new initiative to end the Ethiopian-Eritrean dispute over a
rocky border area, the recent summit of the Organization of the
African Unity proposed for a parley between Eritrean and Ethiopian
foreign ministers in Burkina Faso on August 2.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have accused each other of incursions
since bloody clashes broke out over a 400-square kilometer rocky
triangle of land along their western border.
</P>
<P>
The conflict deteriorated recently, dashing the hope that the
U.S.-led mediation would bring about a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea and Ethiopia, among the world's poorest, are at odds
over at least six areas along their common border. Eritrea gained
independence from Ethiopia in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
