<HEADLINE> East China's Anhui Province Braces for Flood Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 600,000 local residents
worked hard along with soldiers and policemen today to combat
floods in east China's Anhui province, on the lower reaches of the
Yangtze River, in a joint effort to protect their homes from
surging floods.
</P>
<P>
The water level at the Anqing section of the river reached 18.3
metres by 14:00 p.m. today, 2.22 metres above the danger line,
according to local flood-control officials.
</P>
<P>
It is forecasted that the water level of the Yangtze across
Anhui Province will be the highest in more than four decades since
1954.
</P>
<P>
So far, 119 cases of emergency have been reported and spotted
along the dikes of the Yangtze in Anhui. Though the cases have
been dealt with properly, they have victimized 2.8 million local
residents with 4,600 hectares of farmland submerged.
</P>
<P>
A state of emergency has been announced by the provincial
government on Monday, with 2,000 policemen and officers and men of
the Chinese People's Liberation Army already deployed in the areas
where there are hidden dangers and great risks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
