<HEADLINE> HK Can Be Developed Into Technology Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Talents come first in developing
Hong Kong into a technology center of the orient, a high-tech
investor said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Hsu Ta-lin, chairman of the venture capital firm H &AMP; Q Asia
Pacific, said that the government should tap the talents from the
Chinese mainland and abroad by giving them special immigration
treatment.
</P>
<P>
On top of the immigration relaxation, the government should set
up a public market specifically for the technology enterprises to
raise money, provide them affordable land and preferential
taxation, according to the person who heads one of Asia's largest
venture capital and private equity firms.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon co-hosted by the Chief Executive's
Commission on Innovation and Technology and the Hong Kong Venture
Capital Association, Hsu pointed out that Hong Kong enjoys many
favorable conditions in becoming the "Silicon Harbor of the
Orient."
</P>
<P>
Always proud of changing fast, Hong Kong has the
entrepreneurial spirit, well developed private and public market
financing, and good living environment, said Hsu.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the city has started the high-tech development
"in a right way" by setting up the high-level commission to advise
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa on measures to be taken to drive
forward innovation and technology developments in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Comprising 14 people and headed by Professor Chang-Lin Tien,
the commission held its first meeting on March 23. It will submit
an interim report to Tung by the end of September and conclude all
the work within 12 to 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
