<HEADLINE> HK Removes 40-percent Ceiling on Property Lending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) Tuesday withdrew its "40 percent guideline", under which
banks had to limit their lending to the property sector to no more
than 40 percent of their total loans.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA announced Tuesday that it withdrew the guideline --
which was introduced in early 1994 when property lending was
soaring -- because it was less relevant to current market
conditions. The property market is no longer overheated and banks
are now much more restrained in their lending to borrowers.
</P>
<P>
"The 40 percent guideline has served its purpose and it is now
appropriate that it should be withdrawn," said David Carse, deputy
chief executive of the HKMA.
</P>
<P>
But he added: "This does not remove the need for authorized
institutions to manage prudently the risks in their property
lending." Banks should also apply prudent lending criteria, such
as the maximum 70 percent loan-to-value ratio on residential
mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
The amount of gross new loans made in June fell slightly, so
did the average size of new loans, according to the latest
residential mortgage survey released by the HKMA Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The loan delinquency ratio, measured by the ratio of mortgage
loans overdue for more than three months to total outstanding
mortgage loans, was 0.29 percent in June. David Carse said that
figure confirmed the continuing high quality of residential
mortgage loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC FMs End Meeting, Shun Political Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Tuesday ended
their two days of deliberations here on trade and economic
cooperation within the grouping, and shunned political issues at
their discussions.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar told a press
conference later that the SAARC foreign ministers discussed "all
the on-going activities of SAARC," including a number of reports
on economic cooperation in various areas.
</P>
<P>
They also prepared the provisional agenda for the grouping's
summit scheduled for July 29-31 and its draft declaration.
</P>
<P>
This year's SAARC summit comes against the backdrop of mounting
tensions in South Asia in the aftermath of the nuclear tests by
India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
Speculation is ripe that the upcoming summit is being
overshadowed by the worsening security situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Under SAARC's charter, bilateral and contentious issues are
excluded from the deliberations of the grouping, but they can be
discussed informally on the fringes of SAARC meetings. Political
observers here said the nuclear issue is expected to figure
prominently at bilateral meetings of SAARC member countries,
although Kadirgamar has said the Colombo summit will focus on
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian
counterpart Atal Bihari Vajpayee are arriving in Colombo Tuesday
for the summit, and they are expected to meet on Wednesday after
the opening of the three-day summit. The leaders of the other four
SAARC members -- Bhutan, Bangladesh, the Maldives and Nepal -- are
also arriving here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Indo-Pakistani bilateral meeting, which will be the first
of its kind since the two countries carried out nuclear tests in
May, is drawing world attention.
</P>
<P>
Kadirgamar said no political issue was raised during the
foreign ministers' meeting and he insisted that SAARC's main
concern was how to speed up economic growth and social progress
and move "as fast as possible" towards greater and enhanced
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the foreign ministers had "substantial discussions" on
a number of reports and draft guidelines on the issues of food
security, information, telecommunications, visa exemption and
SAARC's cooperation with international and other regional
organizations.
</P>
<P>
A visa exemption scheme within SAARC is expected to be
expanded, he said. Arrangements had been made for SAARC foreign
ministers' informal meeting in September in New York during this
year's United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers met during last year's U.N. General
Assembly. Such a meeting is becoming "more formal and more
structured" as they find it "very useful" when they are all in New
York for the U.N. General Assembly, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
