<HEADLINE> Romanian President Goes to Turkey to Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Romania's President Emil
Constantinescu left for Ankara Tuesday morning for a 12-hour visit
to Turkey to enhance relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Constantinescu and his turkish counterpart
Suleyman Demirel is expected to discuss regional matters, press
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has always been Romania's staunch supporter in its bid
for admission in NATO. At the same time, the two countries have
been building an active regional partnership in favor of political
solutions to all the conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
Some economic issues will also be discussed at the meeting.
Both countries are expecting the bilateral trade to reach 1
billion U.S. dollars in 1999 as opposed to 567 million dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Romanian President will also meet with Turkish Prime Minister
Mesut Yilmaz, who visited Romania just a month ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
