<HEADLINE> Indian Prime Minister Leaves for Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee left here Tuesday for Colombo to take part in the
10th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) to be held on July 29-31.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to meet his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz
Sharif on the sidelines of the summit for the first time after the
two countries conducted their nuclear tests in mid May this year.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen before his departure at the airport here,
Vajpayee said that India would strive to develop an understanding
with Pakistan so that the two neighboring countries could live
together as brothers by solving all problems peacefully.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the resumption of Indo-Pak talks, stalled
twice since 1994 due to the dispute over the Kashmir issue,
Vajpayee said the dialogue would be resumed at Colombo where
modalities would be decided.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting likely on July 29, both the prime
ministers of India and Pakistan are expected to discuss all eight
outstanding issues including Kashmir and peace and security which
the two sides had identified during the foreign secretary level
talks in Islamabad on June 23 last year.
</P>
<P>
A signed article here said that the meeting between the
Indo-Pak prime ministers would be the most important among the
exchanges between the seven South Asian heads of State and
government.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
