<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Malaysia Fall 13 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's tourist industry
was the worst affected by the current problems with tourist
arrivals declining by 13 percent from 7.1 million in 1996 to 6.2
million in 1997, Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister Sabbaruddin
Chik said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the factors that affected tourist arrivals in Malaysia
were the economic slowdown, currency crisis, cholera, problems in
Malaysia-Singapore relations and negative reports by foreign
media, he said at a dialogue with tourist industry personnel
including representatives of hotels, tour companies and bus and
taxi operators here.
</P>
<P>
However Malaysia can still earn the projected 15.7 billion
ringgit (about 3.801 billion U.S. dollars) from tourism in the
year 2000 even though the expected number of tourist arrivals has
been revised from 12.5 million to 7.6 million, he told a news
conference later.
</P>
<P>
This could be done through tour packages which would provide
for longer stay in the country by foreign tourists and another
strategy would be to attract more tourists to Malaysia from the
United States, Europe and West Asia whose currencies had
appreciated against the ringgit, Sabbaruddin said.
</P>
<P>
He urged tour operators to step up their efforts to bring in
more tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
