<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Addresses Establishment of Int'l Criminal Court (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese diplomat said
today that the establishment of an international criminal court, a
long-aspired ideal and objective of international community,
represents a new attempt to reinforce cooperation in the battle
against international crime.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Foreign Minister Wang Guangya, who just returned from
Rome after leading a Chinese delegation to the United Nations
Diplomatic Conference of Plenipotentiaries on the Establishment of
the International Criminal Court (ICC), provided background
information on the meeting during an exclusive interview with
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Wang recalled that international military tribunals in
Nuremberg and Tokyo after World War II and the two Ad Hoc
international criminal tribunals set up respectively by the UN
Security Council in the former Yugoslavia (1993) and Rwanda (1994)
were all temporary criminal courts targeted on specific issues,
rather than permanent courts featuring universality.
</P>
<P>
He described the establishment of the ICC as an outcome of the
development of the international political situation.
</P>
<P>
Wang noted that many countries carefully considered problems
surfacing in the operations of the two existing special
international tribunals and in turn advocated the institution of
a permanent international criminal judicial institution featuring
independence, justice, effectiveness and universality.
</P>
<P>
The aforementioned conference, organized by the UN General
Assembly on December 15, 1997, is expected to finalize and approve
the statute, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
The ICC statute was passed during the conference held at the
headquarters of the UN Food and Agricultural Organization in Rome
between June 15-July 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Addresses Int'l Criminal Court (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang explained the Chinese government's attitude by noting that
China has always understood and supported the establishment of an
independent, just, effective and universal international criminal
court, which is complementary to the state judicial system and the
cooperative international criminal and judicial systems.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese delegation actively participated in the
entire negotiation process and contributed to the enactment of the
ICC statute.
</P>
<P>
The speciality of crimes ICC rules listed concerning state
judicial sovereignty prompted China to advocate caution concerning
stipulations on major issues in order to ensure the court's
independence and justice, rather than turning the court into an
organ for political struggle, or means for interfering in the
domestic affairs of any country.
</P>
<P>
The primary guideline of the ICC statute centers on the
principle of complementarity, meaning that the court should serve
as a complement of the judicial system in the respective state(s),
and the jurisdictional rights of the court should be based on the
approval of the respective state(s), according to
Wang. Irresponsible and wanton proceedings should be avoided to
greatest possible extent with regard to issues such as the
mechanisms and means of surveys.
</P>
<P>
The effectiveness and authority of the court also depends on
transparent, equal and democratic stipulations which ensure the
unniversal participation of the international community, said
Wang, adding that the statute should in no way conflict with or
contravene regulations enshrined in the United Nations Charter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Addresses Int'l Criminal Court (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secondly, according to Wang, the Chinese delegation harbored
great reservations regarding whether or not war crimes in armed
domestic clashes should be included in the general jurisdiction of
the Court.
</P>
<P>
The delegation held that a nation with a highly-perfected
legal system is fully capable of rendering punishment for war
crimes in armed domestic clashes, and has overwhelming
jurisdiction over the ICC when adjudicating punishment for related
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, the statute's current definition on war crimes in
armed domestic clashes far exceeds stipulations in customary
international law, and the Additional Protocol II to the Geneva
Conventions, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
China has consistently advocated that a nation has the right to
either accept or reject the Court's jurisdiction over related
crimes. The current stipulation provides interim arrangements
concerning the right to accept jurisdiction, but nonetheless
rejects the principle in choice. This fact alone would cause many
countries to falter at the mention of the Court, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the Chinese delegation held reservations concerning
stipulations regarding the functions of the United Nations
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The crime of aggression, which represents an act on the part of
a state, has not as yet been explictly defined by law. Avoiding
indiscriminate bills designed purely for political purposes
requires that the Security Council to determine the existence of
an act of aggression prior to any attempt to prosecute individuals
for criminal responsibility. Wang further noted the requirement is
clearly stipulated in the 39th Article of the UN Charter.
</P>
<P>
However, the statute fails to include clear stipulations in
this regard. Moreover, the statue sets 12-month limit on the
Security Council's right to terminate the Court operation in order
to maintain world peace and effectively perform its duties, he
said. The limit is without a doubt detrimental to the Security
Council which performs functions endowed with in the UN Charter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assistant FM on Meeting for Establishing ICC (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang said that it is a pity the statute was approved by ballot
instead of a unanimity among states.
</P>
<P>
China has hoped that the statute would be passed on the basis
of unanimity reached through consultation, so that the
universality and authority of the court would be guaranteed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Due to differences between their respective judicial systems,
participating countries were divergent on the draft statute, which
made the negotiations an arduous job, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Chinese delegation has attended all the
negotiations and consultations, and consistently emphasized that
the statute for the ICC should reflect the reality of the world
arena and be accepted by the vast majority of states.
</P>
<P>
Wang went on to explain why China voted against the Statute,
saying that firstly, the Chinese delegation could not accept the
general jurisdiction of the ICC as the Statute stipulates.
</P>
<P>
The kind of jurisdiction is not based on the willingness of a
country to accept the Court's jurisdiction, instead, it stipulates
the responsibility of those non-contracting countries without
their agreement, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Thus, it violated the principles guiding sovereign countries,
and also did not accord with the stipulations in the Vienna
Convention on the Law of Treaties between States and International
Organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
