</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Addresses Int'l Criminal Court (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fourthly, Wang said the Chinese delegation also harbored
serious reservations to ex officio power of prosecutors in
investigations.
</P>
<P>
The power not only grants individuals, nongovernmental
organizations and various units the right to prosecute civil
servants and soldiers, but also creates the possibility that
procuratorates and courts will use the power to interfere in
internal affairs of a country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the power of investigation will open the Court to
excessive allegations from both individuals and nongovernmental
organizations so that it can hardly dedicates both manpower and
material resources to only the world's most heinous war crimes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, procurators will face allegations resulting from the
fact that they are constantly required to make political judgments
concerning whether to investigate or prosecute. They will thus be
trapped in a political vortex which makes it impossible for them
to remain truly independent and impartial.
</P>
<P>
Finally, according to Wang, the Chinese delegation held
reservations concerning the definition of crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese government's position fully accords
with customary international law which stipulate that crimes
against humanity happen in periods of war or related emergency
situations.
</P>
<P>
Existing statutes, including the Nuremberg Charter and the
Statute on the Ad Hoc International Criminal Tribunal for the
Former Yugoslavia, clearly stipulate that the related crimes are
applicable only in times of war.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the Rome Statute deleted the highly important
standard for periods of war from the definition of crimes against
humanity. In addition, the list of detailed criminal offences
against humanity far exceeds customary international law and
existing laws. Many offences listed literally belong to the realm
of human rights law.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation held that international society should
refrain from forming a court of human rights, and instead focus on
a criminal court responsible for meting out punishment for those
committing the most heinous crimes in the world. With the addition
of human rights, the ICC would depart from the true goal of its
establishment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Addresses Int'l Criminal Court (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moreover, Wang addressed China's understanding of the status of
the Statute following approval and the nation's attitude towards
its subsequent operations.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the conference was compelled to vote by
ballot readily indicated the lack of a consensus. The balloting
fully demonstrated that a number of countries which are home to
over half the world's population found the statute unacceptable,
along with some permanent members of the Security Council. The
dissent will make it very hard to ensure the universality and
authority of the Statute, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
European nations exhibited extraordinary exuberance over the
statute, with numerous reservations voiced by a large number of
Asian and Arabic nations. The ICC has thus emerged as a regional
issue, according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that many countries refrained from objecting
totally to the statute, but nonetheless clearly expressed
reservations concerning certain stipulations.
</P>
<P>
From an overall perspective, the current statute fails to take
into full account the reality of international community, fails to
address the concerns various countries have with regard to
sovereignty and security interests involving jurisdiction, and
other crucial issues surrounding the new Court.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the Chinese delegation will continue joining the
efforts of the international community to render punishment to
individuals committing the most heinous war crimes, Wang said.
China will continue to pay close attention and participate in the
the work of the ICC Preparatory Commission, apart from involving
itself in the enactment of crucial documents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Property Rights Dispute Between Prisoner and State Company (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, July 28 (Xinhua) - China's first property rights
dispute between Plaintiff Tang Zhenqi, a prisoner, and a
state-owned real estate company enters courts in Dalian.
</P>
<P>
The country has witnessed an outbreak of property disputes
since last fall when the government expanded efforts to reform
state-owned enterprises. The 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China decided to clearly delineate state
property as the first step in streamlining troubled state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first case of its kind involving a prisoner
as the plaintiff," according to an official with the State
Administration of State Property. He added that the case is the
focus of attention nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"The emergence of the case indicates the deepening of economic
reform and the dramatic changes taking place in China's democratic
and legal systems," said Wu Bin, a sociologist with the Liaoning
Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The Liaoning Provincial Bureau of State Property has announced
it will consider dissolution of the case as a major breakthrough
in further delineating state property.
</P>
<P>
Tang, 49, established a real estate firm some five years
ago. However, he proceeded in line with the policy restricting
nongovernment companies from operating in the real estate market
and followed the prevailing widespread practice of subordinating
his venture to a state-owned company -- the Dalian Municipal Real
Estate Company. Over half of collective companies in Dalian have
followed the same practice.
</P>
<P>
Tang operated his business according to the guidelines and
business scope of the parent company, paid annual fees for the use
of its name and focused little attention on personal profits and
losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Property Rights Dispute Between Prisoner and State Company (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two years ago, Tang was convicted of commercial embezzlement
and sentenced to five and a half years imprisonment. The
government's new efforts to clearly delimit state property rights
last fall reminded Tang of the situation of his own company, which
he claims is still worth as much as 20 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The court verdict in no way deprives Tang of his property
rights, despite the fact that he is currently in prison,"
according to his attorney, Chen Dehui. "His appeal is both fair
and reasonable," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that his appeal is the result of the country's new
property rights policy.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the government will handle the case in
accordance with well-defined rules," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shoupeng, an official with the Dalian State-Owned
Property Management Bureau, said the government is closely
examining the matter.
</P>
<P>
"Actual state assets will never be relinquished, and private
property will be protected," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Chinese policies concerning the property of state-owned
enterprises stipulate that disputes will initially be handled by
government state-owned property management bureaus and not the
courts.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the increase in property rights cases in recent
months indicate the changing economic concepts of the general
public.
</P>
<P>
"While businesspeople once focused solely on their right to
profits-involving economic cooperation, they now realize the
importance for clearly defined property rights. The change
represents marked progress," according to Wang.
</P>
<P>
Experts note the delineation work will be far from easy task
since subordinate companies use the intangible assets of parent
companies, including their reputations.
</P>
<P>
"The Dalian State-Owned Property Bureau has invited economic
and legal experts to analyze Tang's case in order to ensure a
scientific and equitable decision," said Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
