<HEADLINE> More Tigers Born in South China's Tiger-breeding Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A five-year-old Manchurian tiger
has given birth to four cubs at the Xiongsen Xionghu (bear and
tiger) Park in Guilin, south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The new arrivals raised the park's tiger population to
100. Xiongsen Xionghu Park is a center engaged in tiger breeding.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of the world's estimated 1,000 tigers have
been bred in captivity.
</P>
<P>
The park has invested some 400 million yuan (48.19 million US
dollars) and scored numerous research achievements to breed tigers.
</P>
<P>
Xiongsen Xiaoghu Park has witnessed the birth of 32 tigers,
including Manchurian, South China and Bengal tigers since January
28 this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
