<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PC Market Worldwide Posts Steady Growth in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide PC industry
continues to post steady growth as shipments surpassed 21.1
million units in the second quarter, up 13.9 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the preliminary statistics from Dataquest, a
California-based market analysis firm, the U.S. market sustained a
double-digit growth, increasing by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
"All companies were hurt to some extent by poor performance in
Asia-Pacific and Japan, and true customer demand in other regions
was masked by inventory reductions," Dataquest said in a report
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. market's growth was led by Dell, Gateway and
Hewlett-Packard, with growth ranging from 73.7 percent to 33
percent. With the merger of Compaq and Digital, the company
maintained the No.1 position, although its lead was cut
significantly. Compaq's shipments in the U.S. market reached one
million units, and its market share was 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, International Data Corp., another U.S. market
researcher, described the second quarter growth as "mediocre" in
the United States and worldwide PC market. According to its
statistics, total U.S. PC-vendor shipments grew 10 percent over
last year and declined one percent sequentially. Worldwide, PC
shipments rose 7 percent over the second quarter of 1997 and
declined 3 percent sequentially, as Western Europe rebounded and
the Asia-Pacific and Japan markets declined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
