<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Countries Urged to Help Revive Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan Tuesday urged the international community, particularly
the industrialized countries, to contribute to the recovery of the
financial crisis-hit Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
Surin issued the call in an address at the plenary session of
the two-day ASEAN's (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Post
Ministerial Conference (PMC) which opened here Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
"A global response to the (financial) crisis is needed, not
only for Asia's recovery, but also for the stability of the global
market and health of the world economy," Surin said.
</P>
<P>
Surin said the current Asian financial crisis, whose impact on
major industrial economies has so far been modest, is "a global
problem" and will have impact on all countries.
</P>
<P>
Surin, whose country was the first to be hit by the currency
crisis last year, urged the industrial countries to help the
affected Asian countries by further opening markets and providing
them with much-needed liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Although the ASEAN economies are on their way to recovery, he
said, "there is still a great need for the industrial countries to
open their markets further for products from ASEAN to ensure that
the recovery is fueled by the strong export growth."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN hopes that the industrialized countries will continue to
stimulate domestic demand and to encourage investment in ASEAN
because of the attractive investment opportunities, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Surin also expressed the hope that the industrial countries
will help recycle capital that flowed out of ASEAN and to extend
long-term credit to the affected countries.
</P>
<P>
He praised China's firm commitment to maintaining the stability
of the RMB as an important contribution to financial stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Attending the PMC are the foreign ministers from the nine ASEAN
member countries -- the Philippines, Thailand, Singapore, Laos,
Myanmar, Vietnam, Indonesia, Malaysia and Brunei -- and the 10
ASEAN dialogue partners.
</P>
<P>
After the plenary session, ASEAN representatives will meet
separately with each dialogue partner. The 10 ASEAN dialogue
partners are the United States, Japan, Australia, China, Canada,
South Korea, Russia, India, New Zealand and the European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
