<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford University to Offer Master's Degree Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Stanford, one of the leading
universities in the United States, begins this fall to offer
Internet classes leading to a master's degree in electrical
engineering, reports from the university said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In the industrial age, we went to school. In the communication
age, the school comes to us," said Andy Dipaolo, director of
Stanford's Center for Professional Development.
</P>
<P>
Stanford officials said about 50 students are expected to be
accepted into the program by the time the virtual effort gets under
way in late September.
</P>
<P>
Most of the prospective students for the online program are
expected to be working professionals who would take three to four
years to complete their degree work.
</P>
<P>
Class handouts, notes, homework and exams all will be posted
electronically. Stanford has linked up with Microsoft and Compaq
to provide the students with state-of-the-art technology needed to
complete the courses.
</P>
<P>
Other schools such as Virginia Tech already offer online
master's degrees, but analysts noted that Stanford is the first
university among the top echelon in the United States to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
