<HEADLINE> Capriati Qualifies in Bank of West Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The former Olympic champion
Jennifer Capriati qualified for the main draw of the 450,000 U.S.
dollars Bank of the West Classic after she upset Argentine veteran
Mercedes Paz 6-2, 6-4 in Palo Alto, California, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Six years after being at the top of her career by winning the
gold medal at the Barcelona Olympics at age 16, Capriati had to
struggle for qualifying the main tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Capriati, 133rd in the world, had later
suffered shoulder and elbow injuries.
</P>
<P>
Capriati was arrested on drug possession charges in early 1994.
She was off the tour for most of two and half years after that,
and has played only occasionally since she returned to Grand Slam
play at Roland Garros in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I'm trying to get back to the top and that's what I really
want," said Capriati. "I'm being more serious. I need to play
better and be more consistent."
</P>
<P>
Capriati will meet fellow American Corina Morariu on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Former Stanford student Lilia Osterloh, who won the 1997 U.S.
national collegiate singles title, lost to 25-ranked South African
Joannette Kruger 1-6, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Fang and Thailand's Tamarine Tanasugarn reach the
second round after Li upset France's Nathalie Dechy 4-6, 6-4, 6-3,
and Tanasugarn beat Japan Yuka Yoshida 6-0, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
