<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Jobless Rate Hits Five-Year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel's unemployment hit a
five-year high of 9.3 percent in May, with 210,700 people out of
work, according to the latest official figures.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment has been on rise since the beginning of the year
and there is no indication so far showing the rise trend can be
curbed soon, said a report released by the Central Bureau of
Statistics available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said continued strong growth in the civilian labor
forces helped raise the jobless rate, which was recorded at 9.1 in
April and 8.6 in February respectively.
</P>
<P>
The labor force grew at an annual rate of 1 percent in
January-April, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government's "failed economic policy" has been widely
held responsible for the high jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
"The terrible figures...obligate the government to immediately
change its economic policy and devote the necessary resources to
creating new jobs," Histadrut (Labor Federation) Chairman Amir
Peretz was quoted in Tuesday's Haaretz daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The unemployment problem is at the top of the treasury's list
of priorities in constructing its economic policy for 1999,"
Finance Minister Ya'acov Neeman has said.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Israel said the best way to reduce unemployment was
to cut state budget while expanding the proportion of input in
infrastructure, research and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Water Level Keeps Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The water level of mighty Yangtze
River at the section downstream Hankou is continuing to rise at a
daily rate between 0.05-0.15 meter, an official of the State
Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters (SFCDRH) said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Hankou Hydrologic Station shows that the
water level there has risen to 28.84 meters at six A.M. today,
2.54 m. above the danger mark. The rate of water flow was 68,400
cubic m. per second.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Jiujiang Hydrologic Station climbed to 22.8
m. by six this morning, 0.15 m. higher than yesterday's level or
0.6 m. above the record height.
</P>
<P>
A SFCDRH report says that the water level at Poyang Lake in
east China's Jiangxi Province still keeps rising, reaching 22.35
m. by six A.M. today, 0.55 m. higher than the record level. The
level of Dongting Lake in Hunan Province dropped to 35.4 m. at six
this morning after staying at the historical height of 35.48
m. for 12 hours. The water level of the two lakes has maintained
above the danger mark for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the water level at Nenjiang river in northeast China
and Xijiang River in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region have
surpassed the danger level and is expected to rise further.
</P>
<P>
The China National Power Corporation issued an emergency
circular today, urging all departments and provinces to give top
priority to flood relief and rescue work and ensure power supply.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
