<HEADLINE> Australia Welcomes China's Defense White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Defense Ministry
Tuesday welcomed the release of China's defense White Paper,
saying it was a contribution to regional security transparency and
confidence building.
</P>
<P>
Australia had encouraged other regional countries by providing
practical assistance to issue such equivalent statements of
defense policy, a spokeswoman for Defense Minister Ian McLachlan
said.
</P>
<P>
"Senior Australian defense officials briefed China on
Australia's Strategic Policy 1997 (ASP 97) after its release, and
we look forward to discussing the new White Paper with senior
Chinese People's Liberation Army officers when they visit
Australia in August for the second annual regional security talks
between defense organizations."
</P>
<P>
"The importance of such dialogue was agreed between Ian
McLachlan, Defense Minister, and the Chinese Defense Minister
General Chi Haotian when he visited Australia in February 1998.
General Chi then advised us that a second white paper was in
preparation."
</P>
<P>
In its White Paper, released Monday, the Chinese government
outlined a defense policy based on ending Cold War mentality, with
a promise not to use growing economic might to expand its
territory.
</P>
<P>
"Even when China becomes strong and powerful in the future, it
will by no means take to the road of foreign aggression and
expansion," the State Council said in the 30,000-character paper.
</P>
