<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Prices Down To Seven-Year Lows In U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Wheat future prices plunged
to seven-year lows on the Chicago Board of Trade on concerns about
a supply glut that would push the prices below two U.S. dollars a
bushel in coming weeks, said reports reaching here late in the day.
</P>
<P>
Wheat for September delivery, the contract closest to delivery,
fell 4.75 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 2.605 U.S. dollars a bushel,
the lowest since July 1991. December wheat fell 5 cents to 2.755
U.S. dollars a bushel.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Egypt had purchased 250,000 metric tons
of cheaper French wheat over U.S. products, and American exporters
are struggling with ample supplies and strong competition as Asian
countries cut imports from the United States as a result of
economic troubles in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration announced plans last week to
purchase 80 million bushels of wheat that will be given away to
poor countries in a bid to boost prices. But the figure is too low
to have a serious effect on prices, said Harry Cleberg, president
and chief executive of Farmland Industries, largest U.S.
farmer-owned cooperative.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Agriculture Department estimates farmers will harvest
a total of 2.52 billion bushels of wheat this year when weak
domestic demand and export demand is now 25 percent below normal.
</P>
<P>
Cash prices are already as cheap as two U.S. dollars a bushel
in some areas and analysts say futures may also reach that
threshold in the next few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
