<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform College Entrance Exam System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Education
announced today that it will introduce trial reform into the
college entrance exam system in selected provinces in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
The reform will change the design of test questions and the
arrangement of test subjects, according to Vice-Minister of
Education Zhou Yuanqing.
</P>
<P>
The annual national exam attracts millions of Chinese young
people hoping to attend college and is one of the most important
events for every Chinese family.
</P>
<P>
A small handful of people survive the fierce competition and
eventually enter a university with an opportunity to change their
fate. Achieving the goal requires over 200 million primary and
high school students to struggle with mountains of books and test
papers.
</P>
<P>
Media and educational experts have long complained that the
creativity of students is being stifled and they are, in fact
being hurt both physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the reform will introduce the "Three plus X"
method under which required subjects will include only the Chinese
language, mathematics and a foreign language, and not the five
subjects on the existing exam.
</P>
<P>
Universities will either select one or several test subjects to
supplement the three requirements, and students will choose their
favorite university and subjects.
</P>
<P>
"More freedom will be available for both the universities and
the students," said Zhou, adding the reform will be introduced
first in developed provinces such as Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
More questions will be designed to test the flexibility and
comprehensive capabilities of students, as well as their
understanding of the Chinese economy and society. This in turn
will provide fewer opportunities for students pursuing high marks
based on memorizing boring textbook materials.
</P>
<P>
However, the national unified exam will basically retain its
current form, said Zhou, adding that it will neither be divided
into several tests, nor will it be held several times, as some
people have suggested.
</P>
<P>
China's higher education exam was banned during the "Cultural
Revolution," a period which witnessed the persecution of
intellectuals. The exam was reinstated in 1977 in line with Deng
Xiaoping's instructions for respecting knowledge in order to
modernize China.
</P>
<P>
China has some 1,000 universities and colleges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
