<HEADLINE> Talks Between Pak-Indian PMs to Focus on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming talks between
the Pakistani and Indian leaders will focus on the resumption of
dialogue and issues of peace and security particularly in the
background of nuclearization of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made here Tuesday by Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif before his departure for Colombo, Sri Lanka,
to attend the 10th Summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SARRC) scheduled for July 29 to 31.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said in a statement that the SAARC summit is being held
at a time of momentous development in this region.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan will be playing an active and constructive role in
the summit," he added.
</P>
<P>
The summit, according to Sharif, is likely to focus on the
consideration of the report presented by the Group of Eminent
Persons which was established by the Ninth SAARC Summit in Male
last year at Pakistan's initiative.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Eminent Persons was established to undertake a
comprehensive appraisal of SAARC with a view to further vitalizing
the association as well as on collective efforts to enhance state
and economic cooperation among the member states.
</P>
<P>
The Male summit had agreed on the idea of informal political
consultation with the objective to promote mutual trust and
confidence among the member states.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that it will be Pakistan's endeavor that the
Colombo Summit Declaration contains sound prescriptions for
fruitful interaction among the member states in the identified
areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Nawaz Sharif is scheduled to meet with his Indian counterpart
Atal Bihari Vajpayee Wednesday night. It will be the first top
level encounter after the nuclear tests by the two South Asian
nations in May.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharif said that he will pay a two-day visit to the
Maldives on July 31 after attending the SAARC summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
