<HEADLINE> CPP Leads in Cambodia's Parliamentary Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But the NEC said the results were "temporary" and it reserved
the right to "correct the figure."
</P>
<P>
The NEC based its assessment on counting some of the ballots in
two major constituencies in eastern Cambodia, out of a total of 23.
</P>
<P>
NEC spokesman Samraing Kamsan told reporters that the NEC would
not be able to release complete initial results until August 1.
</P>
<P>
Only the NEC has the authorization to announce election results
and results released by any other party were considered "invalid,"
the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, the CPP said it had pocketed more than half of
the seats in the 122-member National Assembly in Sunday's
election.
</P>
<P>
A CPP senior official said the figure was based on what CPP
members had obtained in each counting office.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) said the partial results collected by
its observers late Monday showed the CPP garnered 50 seats,
followed by Prince Norodom Ranariddh's Funcinpec with 43 and SRP
with 29.
</P>
<P>
Among the 39 political parties registered in the election, the
CPP, Funcinpec and the SRP are three major contenders for
political power in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Under Cambodia's constitution, a party needs a two-thirds
majority in the National Assembly, or 82 seats, to form a
government.
</P>
<P>
If no party wins the required quorum, the new government will
be a coalition with the largest party naming the prime minister.
</P>
