<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Students Receiving Education through </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Students at the University
of Dar es Salaam and the Tanzania Open University have started to
receive education through satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
Under the new education program, the students are able to sit
in Dar es Salaam classrooms and attend lectures given by teachers
in the United States, Canada and Ireland, with special facilities
connected with satellite systems, Daily News said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The students can also raise questions to the lecturers, it
said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the World Bank-funded program is only
benefiting students based in Dar es Salaam, the paper quoted the
Minister of Science, Technology and Higher Education, Jackson
Makweta, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who was tabling 1998/99 budget estimates of his
ministry at the National Assembly in the central city of Dodoma
on Monday, said that plans are underway to extend the program to
students in other areas.
</P>
<P>
He also said the ministry is preparing a bill seeking the
establishment of an institution to oversee the provision of loans
to students of higher learning institutions.
</P>
<P>
Makweta said the independent organ is necessary as the
ministry faced numerous problems in disbursing the loans.
</P>
<P>
He added a special committee has been formed to examine
problems in higher education and propose better ways of running
universities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister said institutions of higher learning
planned to increase the student intake which is too low compared
with universities in east and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the University of Dar es Salaam, the intake should be
increased to 9,300 in the year 2002 from 4,131 at present.
</P>
<P>
Makweta request the parliament to approve 31.1 billion
shillings (4.6 million U.S. Dollars) for the ministry's budget in
the 1998/99 fiscal year, 26.6 billion of which will be for
recurrent expenditure and the rest for development projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
