<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Proposes 7 Sites for World Heritage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is making efforts to
include three national parks and four cultural sites into the
World Heritage List of UNESCO, Education Minister Najib Tun Razak
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three parks are the Pahang National Park, the Kinabalu
National Park and the Gunung Mulu National Park in Sarawak while
the four cultural sites are the Bujang Valley in Kedah, Kota
Melaka (Malacca), the Niah Caves in Sarawak and the Acheh
Street-Armenian Street Enclave in Pulau Pinang, he said.
</P>
<P>
Even though Malaysia is a signatory to the Convention
Concerning The Protection of the World Cultural and Natural
Heritage, it has yet to list any site in the world list, Najib,
who is also president of the UNESCO Malaysia National Commission,
said after opening a seminar on the heritage list in Pulau Pinang,
according to the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Bernama said Malaysia was expected to submit its nominations
for inclusion in the list before July 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
Najib said UNESCO's aim in having such a list was to preserve
such sites throughout the world for the benefit of humankind and
also because these places could bring income from tourism.
</P>
<P>
Noting that since the convention was ratified in 1972, the
World Heritage Committee has listed 516 heritage sites in 108
countries and regions with the list still expanding, he said there
was an imbalance in the list with more than half of the sites
listed being taken from Europe and something must be done to check
this domination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
