<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auckland Airport Shares Listed in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Auckland International
Airport shares started trading Tuesday morning in the New Zealand
share market at a 25 cents premium per share, the local TV station
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Auckland International Airport, the biggest and busiest
airport in New Zealand, used to be owned by the New Zealand
government for 51.6 percent shares of the airport's total and by
the local authorities in Auckland region for the remaining 48.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand government began selling its 51.6 percent
holding (about 217 million shares) on July 1, and got 390 million
New Zealand dollars (over 200 million U.S. dollars) from the
public sale at an issue price of 1.8 New Zealand dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The local TV station reported Monday that 60 percent of the
government's shares were bought by New Zealanders and the
remaining 40 percent by overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, the New Zealand government initiated an economic
reform. One of the main measures for the reform was to sell
stagnant state-owned enterprises in order to break their
monopoly, inject new vigor into them and enhance their
competitiveness in international and domestic markets.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, the New Zealand government has sold a
number of big firms, such as Telecom, and railway and forestry
companies.
</P>
<P>
In the wave of selling the Auckland International Airport,
conflicting opinions and suggestions have been raised on the
issues of the sales of the Wellington International Airport, the
Auckland port, and a state-owned power company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0221 </DOCNO>
