<HEADLINE> Iran's Weekly Office Attacked by Fire Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The office of the Iranian weekly
Khaneh (House) in Tehran was attacked by two unidentified persons
with a fire bomb, local daily Iran News reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The attack at Monday noon caused a minor fire, which was put
out by the occupants in the building, owned by the House of Young
Journalists (HYJ), publisher of the weekly, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after the weekly was accused of publishing a
letter from one of its readers on July 15, which was believed to
have insulted Iran's late supreme leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
Following the attack, the HYJ received an anonymous phone
caller threatening that it would face more serious violence
unless the weekly changes its attitude and performance.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance
immediately deplored the attack, noting that those against the
weekly's articles should pursue the matter through proper and
legal channels and refrain from taking individual action.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed official from the ministry was quoted by Iran News
as saying that this case would be considered by the press
supervisory board.
</P>
<P>
The HYJ once operated under the direct supervision of the
ministry, the official said, but it became independent in
October, 1997 following a change in the ministry's management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
