<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo Tuesday
on buybacks following Monday's steep losses with the key Nikkei index
closing above 16,000.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 170.18 points, or 1.07
percent, from Monday's close to end at 16,114.54. On Monday, the index
plunged 417 points or 2.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 8.24 points or 0.67 percent to
1,242.2.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section was thin at an estimated 350 million
shares, down from 378.38 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Real estate, steel, and food and beverage issues were among the
many sectors which posted gains. A wave of business tie-ups and more
clues regarding the new cabinet also boosted market confidence,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Nissan Diesel Motor and Nissan Motor rose following an announcement
Monday that Nissan Diesel and Daimler-Benz AG will together develop
and produce a light commercial truck for the world market.
</P>
<P>
News that Sumitomo Bank and Daiwa Securities Co. will jointly form
a new firm to wholesale securities also sent the shares of both firms
higher.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers outpaced
losers 662 to 409, with 195 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
