<HEADLINE> U.S. Promises to Help With Asia's Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said here Tuesday that her country will continue to help
Asian countries hit by the financial crisis achieve economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
"America's policy is clear. We call for reform, but we will
also do all we can to help countries that are being hurt by the
crisis and that are committed to reform," she said at the ASEAN
Post-Ministerial Conference Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the international community "has both a
self interest and responsibility to help," saying American
companies have more than 130 billion U.S. dollars at stake and
U.S. economic growth has already slowed down because of the Asian
downturn.
</P>
<P>
Albright told foreign ministers from the ASEAN member countries
and dialogue partners, "Together, we represent a community of
interest and we have no greater common interest than in speeding
this region's recovery."
</P>
<P>
After citing the assistance that has been already provided to
the affected Southeast Asian countries, she said however that
official assistance can only help countries in this region get
through the worst days of the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We also have to recognize that it is not going to solve the
deeper, long-term problems they face. The crisis is not going to
be resolved by aid alone," She said.
</P>
<P>
Albright urged the affected countries to make efforts to
attract long-term committed capital back to this region, saying
foreign direct investment "offers many tangible benefits"
including providing more jobs with higher wages, making possible
advances in technology and productivity and spurring exports and
foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is ready to work with its partners in this
region to encourage renewed direct investment in their economies,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state also called for the resumption of
export-led growth in the region and asked industrialized countries
to keep their markets open. She expressed the hope that Japan will
"continue to move in the direction of policies that stimulate
domestic demand, restructure its banking sector and reduce
regulation of the economy."
</P>
<P>
She said her country will also cooperate with ASEAN nations in
areas such as the environment, migration and fighting drug
trafficking to enable the latter to return to economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
