<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Create Gem Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is striving to create a gem
market in the country and a system to directly sell gems abroad in
an effort to develop its gems services.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper New Light of Myanmar Tuesday quoted
Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the Myanmar
State Peace and Development Council, as saying that the government
has granted rights to local gem merchants, calling for cooperation
between the government and the merchants to share the benefits
gained.
</P>
<P>
A gem market known as the Panglong in Yangon is being
established to become a gem trade center in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar promulgated a new Gemstone Law in September 1995,
allowing local entrepreneurs to produce, transport and sell
finished gemstones and manufacture jewelry at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Before the period, the State Gems Enterprise was the sole
organization which had the rights for the activities.
</P>
<P>
In addition to allowing local private sector to mine gems in
the country, the government has also set up joint ventures with
companies from Thailand and Malaysia for the operation.
</P>
<P>
Since Myanmar's jade and gems are well known in the world, the
country holds gems emporiums annually, fetching a total of more
than 260 million U.S. dollars up to the 35th event in March this
year since 1964 when the first emporium was initiated.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the output value of Myanmar's
mining sector, which include gems and jade, rose 1.5 percent in
1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March and the production of
gems and jade in the year went to 24.7 million carats and 2.7
million kilos respectively.
</P>
<P>
The export of gems amounted to 25 million dollars in the
previous 1996-97, the statistics added.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, rich in precious stones such as gems, jade and diamond
along with other mineral resources, need capital investment and
technical know-how for the exploitation and utilization to
accelerate its economic development.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1988, three new gem lands were discovered in Myanmar
which are the Nawarat (Pyinlon), Namsa and Mongshu in addition to
the old Mogok and Mokaung. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
