<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: S. Korean Won on Rise, Exports Hurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Further rise in the value of South
Korean won against the U.S. dollar is believed to deal a severe
blow to the nation's export if the government fails to intervene.
</P>
<P>
The won went up to 1,209 against the dollar Monday, a new high
since the country signed a deal with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) for a rescue loan of 58 billion dollars last December.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been swept by a financial crisis triggered by
corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions in
late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the already worsened export climate while the nation
remains in the so-called IMF period, the strengthening won has put
enterprises on extreme nerves after two-month straight decline in
export.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said if the won keeps on the 1,200 level, it is
impossible for Seoul to hit its targeted trade surplus of 50
billion dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Export, a vital way for the nation to tide over the financial
crisis, is expecting an ever worsening climate due to the won
appreciation and banks' move to discontinue new financing amid a
whirlpool of drastic restructure in the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Setting export prices with the won-dollar exchange rate at
1,400, exporters are also expected to suffer losses due to the
200-won gap in the foreign exchange rate. Most South Korean
companies view an exchange rate between 1,360 and 1,400 as
desirable to secure profits and upkeep competitiveness in the
international markets.
</P>
<P>
Because of the rising won, foreign buyers have consistently
asked to lower the export prices, which caused South Korean
exporters unable to maintain profitability.
</P>
<P>
A rising currency usually reflects the strength of an economy,
but it seems not the case in won's current rally.
</P>
<P>
"The won's strength is unusual in view of the economic crisis
and most Asian currencies, including the Japanese yen, remaining
weak," said an expert of the Hyundai Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
There are few signs that the South Korean economy is improving
drastically, and the nation is still struggling to carry out
reform programs, including restructuring the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
What has pushed up the won? Analysts and economists attributed
the won surge to an abundance of the dollar on the market stemmed
from an increasing current account surplus and shrinking demand
for the dollar amid corporate and financial restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Some economists also attributed it to the rescheduling of
short-term debts into long-term ones, which resulted in the
reduction of immediate demand for the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserve reached a record high of
38.9 billion dollars on July 15. The current account surplus stood
at 23 billion dollars as a result of the trade surplus in the
first half of 1998, and foreign currency deposits at financial
institutions rose up to 11 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
More dollars are expected to flow into South Korea as
foreigners have begun to buy out or merge local companies.
</P>
<P>
Exporters, who are worried about their competitiveness, have
pushed the government to move ahead of the won' further rise.
</P>
<P>
They have alleged that they will lose their competitive edge if
the won remains below 1,300 level. A survey by the Korea
International Trade Association described a 1,380 level as
"appropriate."
</P>
<P>
However, some economists have expressed different views. They
said it would be beneficial for the won to further appreciate.
The Korea Institute for Industrial Economics and Trade pointed to
1,150 as the optimal won-dollar exchange rate and said a strong
won will reduce the costs of imports.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government, which had banned buying the
greenback for speculative purpose since last November, allowed
customers to buy dollars without proving that they need the
currency on actual demand.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet clear whether the government will directly
intervene in the foreign exchange market, although it said it will
leave the won's fate to the market force.
</P>
<P>
However, most observers predicted that the government will
directly intervene the foreign exchange market, as the United
States and Japan did in joint efforts to slow the yen depreciation
last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meeting in U.S. City on Geographic Information System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Projected to be indispensable
in the 21st century, a type of information technology is drawing
over 8,000 specialists around the world to southern California.
</P>
<P>
At the focus of the annual conference starting Monday in San
Diego is geographic information system, or GIS, with pervasiveness
predicted by the organizers to be just as the Internet is today.
</P>
<P>
GIS is a computer-based tool integrating common database
operations, such as query and statistical analysis, with the
visualization and geographic analysis offered by maps.
</P>
<P>
It is used to map and analyze things and events on earth.
</P>
<P>
What makes San Diego, the second largest city in California,
standing out to host the five-day GIS event is its status as one
of the pioneers in the United States in applying the technology.
</P>
<P>
The city and county of San Diego since 1984 have developed a
system using a computerized base map to locate 832,300 assessor's
parcels, 35,700 street lights, 501 schools, 64 eagle nests, etc.
</P>
<P>
Currently with 50 gigabytes of information, equivalent to the
storage of 90 CD-ROMs, such a GIS system produces maps for area
planners, utility crews, budget analysts and private industries.
</P>
<P>
Over years, San Diego has spent 12 million U.S. dollars to
collect and standardize the geographic data, plus millions more on
annual basis to update local governments' information files.
</P>
<P>
The uses of GIS varies. San Diego city water crews, for
instance, can pinpoint a pipeline break on a digitized map on
their laptop computers, make repairs and download the record of
the repair into the city mainframe computer for future reference.
</P>
<P>
Now at some World Wide Web sites on the Internet, the vast
computer network accessible worldwide, mapping services are
available to point out the best driving route between two places.
</P>
<P>
As for the future, GIS researchers imagine that it will soon be
possible, via the Internet, to call up a map, locate a specific
property, download a photo and even watch a video showing people
and vehicles outside a certain building.
</P>
<P>
Combined with signals transmitted from global positioning
system (GPS) satellites, it might eventually be possible to
geocode any person or article and local it within seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
