<HEADLINE> Indian Airlines Face Negative 5 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The recession in the domestic
aviation industry is set to worsen with the industry heading for a
negative growth in 1998-99 fiscal year (April 1 1998-March 31
1999), The Economic Times said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sluggish economy in the country is showing no sign of an
immediate revival and the writing on the wall is clear to the
domestic aviation industry. All major operators are now resigned
to a negative five percent growth in passenger traffic in 1998-99
against the eight percent growth in passenger traffic projected
for the fiscal year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Every airline has experienced a 10-15 percent drop in seat
factor. They witnessed a seat factor of little over 60 percent
during traditional peak season for tourist travel in May and June.
Alliance Air Managing Director Vinoo Kashyap said the situation
was quite bleak and the coming months do not hold any promise.
</P>
