<HEADLINE> Thailand Focuses on Social Issues in 5th IMF Letter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will focus on social
issues especially the mounting unemployment problems in its fifth
letter of intent to the International Monetary Fund (IMF), a
government source said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda also
said that Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai was very concerned about
the employment situation and wanted it included in the fifth
letter of intent to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The number of unemployed people in Thailand surged after the
financial crisis broke out last July. In the first six months of
this year, jobless people have already exceeded two million, a
number the government estimated for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
In view of the worsening situation, the Finance Ministry has
prepared several measures to help ease the problems, including
debt restructuring for troubled businesses, Tarrin informed.
</P>
<P>
If the measures succeeded, businesses would continue and staff
would be able to keep their jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has also been trying to solve
unemployment problems by injecting five billion baht (125 million
U.S. dollars) into a social safety net program to train some
750,000 skilled labor nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The government was also pushing for a deficit budget for fiscal
1999 in its letter of intent to the IMF so that more money can be
diverted into the labor sector, the source said.
</P>
<P>
According to Tarrin, the fifth letter of intent will also touch
on education, public health and the agricultural sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
