<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Exports up 7.3 Percent in First Seven Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's exports are expected to
amount to 5.5 billion U.S. dollars in the first seven months of
the year, a 7.3 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports could reach 6.9 billion dollars, a 1.9 percent increase,
said a report released by the General Department of Statistics on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry of trade said the export growth in the first seven
months of 1998 was at a four-year low compared with figures in
previous periods.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Asia is blamed for Vietnam's export
slowdown, for 70 percent of the country's exports are to Southeast
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's exports to Japan, South Korea and other Southeast
Asian countries have declined markedly as these countries were
severely hit by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has decided to revise downward several economic targets
for 1998. The targeted export growth for 1998 now has been cut to
10 percent from the original 23 percent. This amounts to about 10
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
