<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Win Women's Soccer Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States won the women's
soccer crown at the Goodwill Games here Monday night, beating
China 2-0 in the final.
</P>
<P>
The heroin of the U.S. team was the young and veteran striker
Mia Hamm, who in the 66th minute blasted the ball home from a
dozen meters off the left post after receiving a pass from
midfielder Kristine Lilly.
</P>
<P>
About 20 minutes later, Mia, described later by the Chinese
goalie Zhao Yan as an "exceptional player," scored again from 35
meters.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team, with the retirement of a few key players this
year, showed some weakness in cooperation and defense. The new
goal keeper Zhao Yan did an excellent job and saved a number of
goals during the first half of the match.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese women's soccer proved their strength today, although
we lost to a very strong American team," said Chinese coach Ma
Yuanan.
</P>
<P>
He said that China had two very good opportunities but lacked
finishing power.
</P>
<P>
The Americans took good advantage of their chances, he said,
adding that he was pretty pleased with the performance of his team.
</P>
<P>
For the past few years, the two teams met in a number of
international games, with the United States winning the most
matches.
</P>
<P>
Norway carried home the bronze medal after winning the penalty
kick shoot-out 4-2 against Denmark earlier in the evening. Their
final scores were 5-3. The two teams had tied 1-1 in regulation
time.
</P>
<P>
All these four women teams qualified for the World Cup to be
held in the United States next year.
</P>
<P>
The final match Monday night drew an attendance of 11,307, a
record size in the Goodwill Games history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
