<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Optimistic Over Situation in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan said here Tuesday that peace and development remain the
mainstream of the times and that dialogue and cooperation the
common aspiration of all countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at the annual ASEAN Post-Ministerial Conference
(PMC) here Tuesday morning, Tang noted that "the situation in this
region and the world at large has undergone profound changes"
since the PMC last year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said destabilizing factors are also on the
increase.
</P>
<P>
"Under the impact of the financial storm, the situation in Asia
has become volatile, the momentum of development characterized by
fast economic growth and relative political stability has suffered
setbacks and the efforts to maintain economic security face
unprecedented challenges."
</P>
<P>
But he described the economic woes facing Asian countries as
difficulties on the way of progress, saying whether Asia can
deliver itself from the difficult position depends on various
factors, both internal and external. "A comprehensive analysis of
various conditions gives us every reason to be fully confident in
the future development of Asia."
</P>
<P>
Despite the strong impact of the financial crisis, he said, the
foundation for Asia's development is not seriously damaged and the
economic fundamentals remain sound.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he pointed out that in challenges lie
opportunities. In an effort to address their economic problems,
Asian countries are restructuring their economies, changing the
mode of growth, improving the financial regulatory system and
promoting scientific and technological progress.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister described the market potentials
of East Asia and the rest of Asia as "far from being tapped,"
which he said is "a most favorable factor in ensuring continued
economic growth in Asia."
</P>
<P>
He praised the fine cultural tradition which the Asian people
have created over their long history, such as esteem for
self-respect and self-improvement, hard work and plain living,
diligence and thrift, modesty and studiousness and dedication to
the community and the collective.
</P>
<P>
He declared that Asian countries will be able to bring back
vigor and vitality to their economic development, as long as they
carry on these cultural traditions while drawing upon advanced
achievements of the world civilization in the process of
integrating themselves with the trend of the times.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the recovery and development of the Asian
economy also depend on a favorable external environment. "It
should be noted that the financial crisis in East Asia broke out
against a background of economic globalization, the globalization
of the financial market in particular, even though it does have
something to do with Asia's internal factors."
</P>
<P>
He said the crisis has not only raised a new subject for the
developing countries in their integration with the world economy,
but also posed a new challenge to the work of maintaining the
security of the global economic and financial systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
