<HEADLINE> Cooperation Is Needed to Solve Common Problems in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Prime Minister
Sirimavo Bandaranaike Tuesday said cooperation among South Asian
countries is needed to solve the common problems affecting the
progress and development of the SAARC region.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the occasion of the 10th South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) summit which opens in
Colombo tomorrow, the prime minister said that this is all the
more necessary because problems relating to South Asian countries
are similar in nature.
</P>
<P>
She said that some South Asian countries, which are among the
poor nations of the world, are faced with the problems of rapid
population growth, scarcity of food, diseases and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, a number of other sensitive problems have arisen.
The ethnic problem is one of them. These problems have become so
disastrous as to give rise to internal strife and armed
struggles," the message said.
</P>
<P>
"The increasing complexities of these problems has inevitably
led to a sharp deterioration in the quality of human life in the
region," the prime minister pointed out.
</P>
<P>
She said they should not forget that there were invisible
forces responsible for this state of affairs.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister urged that the SAARC countries should act
with a sense of mutual trust and understanding to make a
cooperative effort to overcome these problems.
</P>
<P>
She believed that through mutual cooperation most problems
could be solved. 
</P>
