<HEADLINE> Brazil Lifts Price Controls on Refinery Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazil decided to lift price
controls Monday on what refineries may charge distributors, and
opened up oil imports to companies other than the state-run oil
company, Petrobras.
</P>
<P>
The decision was signed by Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and will be effective Wednesday. It was expected
to have an immediate impact on prices at the pump.
</P>
<P>
In November 1995, the Brazilian Congress approved a
constitutional amendment on ending Petrobras' 40-year monopoly on
oil production, refining and importing oil. But the government
only recently began to allow other oil companies to operate in
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Almost all oil refined in Brazil comes from Petrobras'
refineries, and has been sold at the set price of 0.34 reals (0.31
U.S. dollars) regardless of prices on the world market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
