<HEADLINE> FM: Chinese Economic Growth Not Affected by Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis in East Asia
will not slow down the pace of China's reform and opening-up, nor
has it done so, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his statement at the ASEAN Post-Ministerial Conference,
which opened its annual meeting here Tuesday morning, Tang said
that as a member of Asia, China is speeding up its efforts to
build a socialist market economic system and bring about a
fundamental change in the mode of economic growth, with a view to
keeping a sustained, rapid and sound development of the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
"A China enjoying political stability, economic growth and
social progress will not only benefit its 1.2 billion people, but
also continue to make important contribution to stability and
prosperity of Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese government "has adopted a highly
responsible attitude in facing up to the challenge of the East
Asian financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
While working to expand domestic demand to boost its economic
growth, he said, China persists in not devaluing its currency, the
RMB, thus making a positive contribution to stabilizing the
regional economy.
</P>
<P>
China has also contributed about 4 billion U.S. dollars as aid
to the Operational Budget of the IMF and has also provided
assistance within its capability to the countries concerned
through bilateral channels.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that China will, as always, pull together with the
East Asian countries in times of trouble and continue its efforts
toward easing off the financial crisis in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tang is here attending the ASEAN Regional
Forum and Post-Ministerial Conference between ASEAN member
countries and dialogue partners from July 27 to 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
