<HEADLINE> EU Confident in ASEAN Despite Regional Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) remained
confident in ASEAN despite the economic difficulties and the
social impacts caused by the ongoing financial crisis in the
region, Austrian Vice Chancellor and Minister for Foreign Affairs
Wolfgang Schussel said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Schussel, speaking on behalf of the EU at the plenary session
of the two-day ASEAN Post-Ministerial Conference, said the
Southeast Asian region has been hit by a serious economic storm
and the crisis has had an impact on the social and political
structures.
</P>
<P>
"The EU is aware that this crisis is more severe and more
difficult to overcome than expected even six months ago and that
the social side effects of the economic crisis have still not
reached their peak, but we do remain confident in ASEAN," he said
in his statement.
</P>
<P>
Since its foundation in 1967, ASEAN has overcome several other
crises and weathered the winds of change, Schussel said. Despite
the present economic and political difficulties, ASEAN will
continue to fulfill its essential function of promoting
cooperation and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We are positive that at the end of this process of economic
and global adjustment, ASEAN will emerge as a stronger and even
more coherent regional grouping prepared to face the tasks for the
21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the EU is willing to provide technical assistance
to help ASEAN survive the current financial crisis if requested to
do so.
</P>
<P>
Schussel said that the EU hopes to increase its cooperation in
all relevant fields with its ASEAN partners, including the ASEAN
Free Trade Area, the ASEAN Industrial Cooperation, the ASEAN
Investment Agreement and other cooperative projects.
</P>
<P>
The EU is one of the 10 dialogue partners of ASEAN. The other
ASEAN dialogue partners include Australia, Canada, China, India,
Japan, South Korea, New Zealand, Russia and the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
