<HEADLINE> Number of Thai Generals Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The number of generals in the
three armed forces of Thailand has dropped from 2,000 in September
last year to 1,859 in April this year, the Bangkok Post reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of those remaining generals, 616 are in inactive posts, the
newspaper quoted a Defense Ministry source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The drop resulted from a policy proposed by Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai, who is also the Defense Minister, of replacing only
75 percent of retired generals from the Defense Ministry, the
Supreme Command and the three armed forces.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, Chuan had asked the three armed forces
to appoint new generals "only in extremely necessary cases" in a
forth-coming military reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also suggested a major-general or a
lieutenant-general take three to five years instead of one to two
years to be eligible for promotion, the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
