<HEADLINE> Austrian Miner Rescued After Stuck Underground for Nine Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- An Austrian miner trapped in a
collapsed mine for nine days was brought to the surface on Sunday
and was miraculously in good health.
</P>
<P>
Austrian television reports said Georg Hainzl, 24, was pulled
up from 60 meters down in a magnesium silicate mine at Lassing,
220 kilometers southwest of Vienna.
</P>
<P>
As shown on the television, He was then taken to a hospital in
Graz, about 200 kilometers southwest of the capital.
</P>
<P>
"It is the miracle of Lassing," provincial governor Waltraut
Klasnic said, while Austrian President Thomas Klestil hailed it a
"victory for hope" and thanked rescue workers for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
Hainzl was trapped on July 17 after a mudslide filled the
mine. It was Austria's worst post-war mining disaster.
</P>
<P>
Officials had given up all hope that Hainzl and 10 other
trapped miners could be alive.
</P>
<P>
The other 10 miners were buried in a second mudslide that
struck when they entered the pit in an attempt to rescue Hainzl.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are continuing to find these 10 miners, but there
appeared practically no hope for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
