<HEADLINE> Number of Child Prostitutes in Thailand Determined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, July 28 (Xinhua) -- In an attempt to end the
decade-old debate over the number of child prostitutes in
Thailand, The Public Welfare Department of the Thai government
announced Monday that only 17,978 people below 18 years of age
were working in the sex trade, not 800,000 as named by some
children's right groups, the Bangkok Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The analysis of previous studies held by several government
and non-government organizations concluded that at any time in
1997 there were 90,916 sex workers in Thailand, 50,636 of whom had
started at an early age.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17,978 child prostitutes, 5,510 are children from
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The department's director-general Irawat Chantharaprasert was
quoted by the Bangkok Post as saying that he would propose to the
Thai Cabinet and Foreign Ministry to use the number as the
official figure in order to end "misleading speculation by the
foreign media which uses it to attack Thailand." 
</P>
</TEXT>
