<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy seen contracting 8.5 percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The Thai economy is expected to
contract by 8.5 percent this year before it recovers to expand a
marginal 0.2 percent in 1999, Bangkok Bank said in a research
report available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the baht is forecasted to move in the range
between 40 baht and 43 baht against the U.S. dollar in the second
half of this year while long-term interest rates are expected not
to decline higher than one percentage point despite the expected
fall of the short-term rate.
</P>
<P>
"the baht movement also depends on other regional currencies
as the baht would be hit if volatility renews," the said.
</P>
<P>
The bank expected that the Thai recession, tight liquidity and
a sharp decline in consumer demand would likely restrain inflation
to about 7.7 percent in 1999 after a projected 10.4 percent
increase in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that expected foreign capital inflows as well as
a bigger fiscal deficit would help stimulate the economy next year
due to further investment and rising private spending.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country's 1999 trade account in baht terms would
post a 5.8 percent surplus of GDP while the current account is
also expected to record a surplus for the second straight year in
1999 of 4.9 percent of GDP against an expected 5.2 percent surplus
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
