<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Observers: Cambodian Election "Free and Fair" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 28 (Xinhua) -- International observers
monitoring the Cambodian election said late Monday that Sunday's
voting was "free and fair," fueling hopes that the election could
be a success.
</P>
<P>
The Join International Observer Group (JIOG) Cambodians said in
a statement that "it is the impression of the JIOG that what could
be observed by us on polling day and counting day was a process
which was free and fair to an extent that enables it to reflect,
in a credible way, the will of the Cambodian people."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the assessment was based on the reports
received from the JIOG's almost 500 international observers in the
field.
</P>
<P>
"A consolidated statement will be made at a later stage, when
these observers have been debriefed after their return to Phnom
Penh and their full reports have been thoroughly analyzed," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the reports received by the JIOG thus far "have been,
in the main, encouraging" and the climate on polling day and
counting day "was peaceful and calm."
</P>
<P>
"In general, the polling achieved democratic standards and on
the day it appears that people felt able to vote without fear of
reprisal," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Cambodians went to polls en masse on Sunday to vote in historic
elections that were expected to give the country a second chance
for peace, stability and a legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian National Election Committee (NEC) reported a
massive voter turnout of more than 90 percent, a much higher
figure than expected.
</P>
<P>
The JIOG's statement said the atmosphere and procedures of the
polling day and counting day, arranged by the Cambodians
themselves, "represent a major achievement and step forward
compared with similar circumstances during the 1993 Cambodian
parliamentary elections."
</P>
<P>
"No serious cases of violence have been reported, nor, at this
stage, any serious irregularities that could have a significant
effect the integrity of the voting process," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the JIOG will continue to observe the electoral process
in the most thorough way possible and believes that all parties
"should accept and honor the results of the election without any
attempt to undermine the original outcome."
</P>
<P>
Partial results are expected to be officially announced as
early as later Tuesday. Initial results collected by unofficial
sources put incumbent co-premier's Cambodian People's Party as
leading in the election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
