<HEADLINE> Europe to Try Harder for Middle East Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima
said here on Monday that the European Union would exert more
efforts to push forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The progress in the peace process will also be necessary for
the security of Europe, Klima said at a joint press conference
with visiting Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Austria currently holds the rotating EU presidency, and Arafat
arrived Monday on a one-day visit to the capital, Vienna, where he
met with Klima, President Thomas Klestil, and Speaker of
Parliament Heinz Fischer.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to make clear that the EU will proceed in a
coordinated way with the United States. We hope that the political
expression of the international community will help to ensure that
the U.S. initiative can also be quickly accepted by Israel," the
chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
Klima reiterated that recognition of the Palestinian rights to
self-determination is a basic policy for Austria and the EU. They
supported the United Nations General Assembly's decision to
upgrade the Palestinian status.
</P>
<P>
Austria would press the EU to continue with a program of
financial aid for the Palestinians, Klima added.
</P>
<P>
Yasser Arafat asked the European Union to increase pressure on
Israel to agree to U.S. proposals on returning more West Bank land
to Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
"We need European and American pressure to get Israel to the
negotiating table," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat welcomed a proposal by Egypt and France to hold a new
international conference on the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
After his meetings in Vienna, Arafat was to go to Paris to meet
with French President Jacques Chirac. 
