<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Willing to Build Stable Relations With Jamaica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINGSTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
on Monday conveyed to Jamaican leaders China's wish for long-term
stable relations of cooperation with Jamaica in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Highly praising the friendship between Jamaica and China,
Governor-General Howard Cooke said his country is willing to
actively push forward bilateral cooperation in all areas.
</P>
<P>
Qian, here since Saturday, expressed his appreciation at the
contribution made by Cooke in pushing ahead Sino-Jamaica relations.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting with Qian, Prime Minister Percival
Patterson said Jamaica and China have been constantly expanding
their relations since mutual diplomatic recognition 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the number of high-level visits to each other is
increasing, Patterson said Jamaica is expecting to continue the
cooperation in international affairs and bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Qian praised the increasingly bigger role Jamaica is playing in
the Caribbean and in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Patterson is scheduled to visit China later this year. Qian
said he believed the planned visit will help promote the relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Qian and Seymour Mullings, deputy prime
minister and minister of foreign affairs and trade, discussed
bilateral ties and international issues at the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Mullings thanked the Chinese government and people for their
assistance and other help over the past years, hoping that
cooperation between his country and China will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Qian told Mullings that it is in the fundamental interests of
the peoples of both countries to improve contacts, increase
understanding, develop friendship and expand cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed appreciation at the one-China policy upheld
by the Jamaican government and its efforts in pushing forward the
relations between China and other Caribbean countries.
</P>
<P>
With a good political relationship and the desire to cooperate,
Qian said, the Chinese government is willing to search for new
ways and areas for cooperation with Jamaica on the basis of
treating each other as equals.
</P>
<P>
China and Jamaica share common or similar views on many
international issues, said Qian, adding Jamaica is an important
country in the Caribbean region.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Fifteen (G-15) African, Caribbean and Pacific
nations will hold its 9th summit in Jamaica next year. Qian said
China supports Jamaica's efforts to promote regional integration.
</P>
<P>
With the globalization of world economy and the integration of
regional economies, it would help boost their power as a whole for
the Caribbean countries to work together and speak in one voice.
</P>
<P>
Jamaica is the last stop of the Chinese vice-premier's
five-Caribbean-nation tour, which has already taken him to
Barbados, Guyana, Trinidad and Tobago, and Cuba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
