<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Reveals Resolving Economic Crisis More Urgent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- The majority of respondents in a
new poll in Indonesia believed that resolving the economic crisis,
not politics, should be the country's top priority, local press
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by the Institute for the Study and
Advancement of Business Ethics, found that 87.3 percent of
respondents wished to see the government defuse the economic
crisis as the priority, compared to 8.4 percent picking political
issues.
</P>
<P>
The poll tallied opinions 5,000 respondents in 10 major cities.
About 70 percent were aged from 26 years to 65 years, with nearly
half of the respondents having at least a high school education.
</P>
<P>
Respondents were asked eight questions, ranging from the
country's most immediate problems, their trust in the government
and the recent riots.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the difficult situation faced by everyone in the
country, 36.6 percent of respondents said lowering prices of basic
essentials was the most pressing need.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been the worst hit by the regional currency
turmoil with the rupiah losing over 80 percent of its value
against the U.S. dollar since July last year. According to the
Central Bureau of Statistics, the number of poor people in the
country has increased from 22.5 million in 1996 to 79.4 million
now.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that as many as 38.9 percent expressed
confidence that the government can solve the economic crisis,
compared to 34.4 percent casting doubt on their ability.
</P>
<P>
On the looting and burning of ethnic Chinese-owned businesses
during mid-May riots in Jakarta and other cities, the majority,
44.4 percent, said that they were very tragic events, and 28.4
percent expressed that they were also humiliating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
