<HEADLINE> Rugby Player's Suspension Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The four-year suspension given to
Canadian rugby player Glenn Ennis for a positive cocaine test has
been overturned on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The application is allowed and Mr. Glenn Ennis is hereby
reinstated to full sport eligibility on the grounds of exceptional
circumstances," adjudicator David Lech wrote.
</P>
<P>
Rugby Canada announced the suspension on June 17 after cocaine
was found in a urine sample taken from Ennis following Canada's
Pacific Rim tournament match against the United States on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Ennis appealed the suspension. A hearing involving Ennis, Rugby
Canada and Sport Canada was held Friday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
Lech's full written reasons will be provided by September 15.
</P>
