<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Specialist Explains Reasons For Yangtze's Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 28 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese specialist speaks about
the river's "stomach" when talking about its middle and lower
reaches and about how they're just too small to hold the large
volume of water from the upper reaches and the tributaries in the
middle and lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shengfu, a senior engineer of the Yangtze River Water
Conservation Committee, said that in the past, the river's
complicated geological conditions, ant holes, or different
embankment structures have all been used as evidence of the
devastating floods that have continued to visit it in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
He warned that disasters can occur whenever the "stomach erupts
because of eating too much."
</P>
<P>
Rains have caused serious flooding over the whole Yangtze Basin
for the fourth time this decade, the second largest flood since
1954, he says.
</P>
<P>
The 6,300-km Yangtze is China's longest river and is known as a
"cradle" of Chinese civilization, along with the Yellow River, the
second longest.
</P>
<P>
In the past 200 years, there has been one devastating flood
recorded every 10 years. The 1931 deluge affected nearly 30
million people, took the lives of more than 140,000, and destroyed
more than 200,000 ha. of farmland.
</P>
<P>
In 1954, flooding affected the lives of more than 10 million
people and left 30,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
For the past several decades, the government and people have
done a great deal to reinforce dikes and dams along the gigantic
river, but its ability to withstand floods is still not good
enough, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The accumulation of mud in the river and its tributaries has
reduced its capacity to hold the overflow, he pointed out, and the
large lakes along the river have been shrinking and small ones
disappearing.
</P>
<P>
Dongting Lake, for instance, has shrunk from over 6,000
sq.km. in 1825 to less than 2,700 sq.km..
</P>
<P>
In Hubei Province, the number of lakes declined from 1,332 in
the early '50s to 843 in the '80s, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that flooding in the Yangtze Basin, which is one of
the most developed areas in the country, can cause tremendous
losses, even when they are not major floods and even though there
may not be a large number of people killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merapi Volcano May Erupt Again in Near Future, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's most active volcano
Mt. Merapi may erupt again in the near future due to magma
pressure from the volcano's core, Antara News Agency Tuesday
quoted a volcanology official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The possibility was necessitating the maintenance of alertness
among residents of areas around the mountain in Central Java, head
of the Center for Research and Development of Volcanic Technology
Mas Ace Purbawinata said.
</P>
<P>
Merapi erupted on July 11, spilling out hot fumes and ashes and
its conditions have prompted local authorities to maintain a
"Merapi alert" state of readiness. The alert status meant that
people living near the mountain had to be prepared to move to
safer places any time.
</P>
<P>
So far, the alert status of Merapi was not being changed
despite the fact that it is frequently emitting clouds of hot gas
to as high as 5,000 meters above the mountain's peak.
</P>
<P>
Merapi's activity entered a critical phase on July 19 as it
spewed out clouds of hot gas as high as 8,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Residents around the volcano reported thick dust falling on
their villages with some closest to the peak saying the dust had
reached a thickness of one centimeter.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people living in the volcano's vicinity have been
suffering from respiratory illness and eye disorders caused by
volcanic ash rains that fell almost every days, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Merapi, 2,968-meter high and one the most active volcanoes in
Indonesia, last erupted in November 1994, killing at least 60
people.
</P>
<P>
Merapi's most destructive eruption this century was in 1930,
when 1,300 people were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0300 </DOCNO>
