<HEADLINE> Canadian Dollar Slides to New Lows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian dollar continued its slide
on Monday, dropping a new record low close of 66.51 U.S. cents on the
North American market.
</P>
<P>
The loonie also set a new trading low against the U.S. dollar,
reaching 66.43 U.S. cents in the afternoon trading, according to
reports here.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks, the currency has set a series of record
low closes.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian dollar is expected to dive further to 66 U.S. cents by
the end of the week unless the Bank of Canada raises interest rates,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
So far, the central bank has resisted the call for the interest
hikes, especially at a time when the Canadian economy is showing signs
of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
Until the Asian financial picture improves, the Canadian dollars
will remain under constant pressure, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The reason is that the Canadian economy still depends on exports of
oil, gas, forest and other commodities, whose prices have been soft as
a result of the Asian crisis, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
