<DOCNO> XIE19980728.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford Offers Master's Degree Completely Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Stanford University in northern
California this fall will become the first major research university
in the United States to offer a master's degree totally online.
</P>
<P>
The new online program will offer 30 courses leading to a master's
degree in electrical engineering. Students are not required to go to
campus at all.
</P>
<P>
For 30 years, Stanford's School of Engineering has offered graduate
engineering degree programs, non-credit courses, certificate programs,
seminars and short courses to distance learners at some 300 companies
using a combination of microwave, videotape, satellite and two-way
digital video technology.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the Stanford Center for Professional Development (SCPD)
has been experimenting with delivery of courses via the Internet.
After a project demonstrated the demand for on-line access among
working professionals, SCPD established Stanford Online to deliver
courses to the desktop of the distance learner. The service already
offers Stanford credit for a variety of on-line courses, but until
now, there have not been enough on-line offerings to allow a student
to obtain an advanced degree in this fashion.
</P>
<P>
"In the industrial age we went to school. In the communication age
the school comes to us," SCPD director Andy DiPaolo said. "Through
Stanford Online we intend to prove this concept by making a portion of
the graduate engineering curriculum available to qualified students
anywhere, anytime and on-demand."
</P>
<P>
About 50 students are expected to be accepted into the program. As
most of them will be working professionals, they are expected to take
three to four years to complete their degree work. Typically, a
master's degree candidate needs only a year or so.
</P>
<P>
The university said that it has linked up with Microsoft and Compaq
to provide the master's degree candidates with state-of-the-art
communications technology.
</P>
<P>
When judged by test scores, Stanford said, studies have shown there
is little or no difference between the performance of distance
learners and on-campus students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
