<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Delivery to Southern Sudanese Hampered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Food delivery by
international relief agencies to 1.2 million people in southern
Sudan is hampered by heavy rains and lack of roads, the U.S.
State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin, spokesman for the State Department, said
distribution problems remain "significant and genuine" because
of a "horrific situation."
</P>
<P>
The 1.2 million people in southern Sudan need 9,500 tons of
food per month. The U.N.-sponsored relief effort known as
Operation Lifeline has increased its heavy-lift air fleet from
two to 11 and has added three new air bases in the area, Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that, barges have also been used but with limited
success, he said, adding that there are numerous problems with
proposals for using a rail line from Khartoum to southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing what we can do in a horrific situation to
support the Sudan peace talks, because ultimately it is only
peace that can break the cycle of famine that has been so
prevalent in Sudan," Rubin said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
